Opening, which has been White's main weapon against 1 e4 e5 at grandmaster
level for some time. White develops the light-squared bishop to an active
square whilst putting pressure on the central e5-pawn by attacking its
defender.} Nf6 (3... a6 {is the other main move.}) 4. O-O ({It is worth noting
that} 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nxe5 {is met by the typical reaction} Qd4 $1 6. Nf3 Qxe4+
7. Qe2 Qxe2+ 8. Kxe2 {with a good game for Black, due to the two bishops and
safer king.}) 4... d6 {Black secures his e5-pawn, but also locks his
dark-squared bishop in. --- EXERCISE: What should White play after Stark's 4...d6?} ({These days the Berlin Defence starting with} 4... Nxe4 {has become all
the rage. Former World Champion Vladimir Kramnik used this opening to
successfully defend against Garry Kasparov in their World Championship match
of 2000. After} 5. d4 (5. Re1 $5) ({and} 5. Qe2 $5 {have become popular ways
to avoid the ending}) 5... Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {the
'Berlin endgame' is reached, which certainly isn't to everybody's taste due to
the early exchange of queens.}) (4... a6 $2 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nxe5 $1 {would now
just win a pawn, as} Nxe4 7. Re1 Bf5 8. d3 {would lead to disaster down the
e-file for Black} ({but not of course} 8. f3 $4 {, weakening the a7-g1
diagonal; indeed,} Bc5+ 9. Kf1 Qd4 {would be a sad end for White.})) 5. d4 $1 {
(ANSWER) White exploits his slight lead in development and safer king position
to try and open some lines and grab the centre.} Bd7 {Black guards against
threats of d4-d5.} 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Bg5 {White finishes the development of his
last minor piece.} ({Note that} 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. dxe5 {would not offer White
much due to} Nxe4 {.}) 7... exd4 {Black decides to release the tension in the
centre.} 8. Nxd4 O-O (8... Nxd4 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Qxd4 O-O {is slightly better
for White, due to his extra space and more active pieces.}) 9. Bxc6 bxc6 {
QUESTION: Hang on a minute - hasn't White just given up the bishop-pair and
opened the b-file for Black's rook? --- ANSWER: Well, yes, he has, but the
problem was that Black was preparing to exchange off the knights and
light-squared bishops with 9...Nxd4. White has created an imbalance 
(bishop-pair for Black; better pawn structure and good knight on d4 for White),
so not everything is in Black's favour.} 10. Qd3 {I am very fond of this queen
move. Her Majesty eyes up the squares a6 and g3 whilst connecting the rooks
and reinforcing the central e-pawn.} Ng4 {Stark looks to relieve some of the
discomfort caused by White's space advantage through exchanges, which is a
normal defensive strategy.} (10... Nxe4 {is a typical tactical motif, trying
to exploit the undefended bishop on g5, but here it simply loses a piece to}
11. Bxe7 (11. Nxe4 $2 Bxg5 {is the idea}) 11... Qxe7 12. Nxe4 {. Note that if
the queen was on d1, this idea may have worked.}) 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 {EXERCISE:
What should White play here? --- ANSWER:} 12. f4 $1 {Controlling the important
e5-square.} f5 {Black decides to fight back in the centre.} ({I would have
preferred} 12... Rab8 13. b3 Rfe8 {, though I still think White is a bit
better due to his central control.}) 13. Rae1 fxe4 {QUESTION: Which is the
best way to recapture? --- ANSWER:} 14. Nxe4 $1 {Centralization! This is a
very important principle to remember. The knight is en route to a better home.}
(14. Rxe4 $6 {is a bit too 'obvious'. Rooks are often just as effective on the
first rank and this is a good example of that. After something like} Qf7 15.
Rfe1 d5 16. Re7 Qxf4 {Black's counterplay is in full swing.}) ({Meanwhile, we
don't want to swap the queens off with} 14. Qxe4 Qxe4 15. Rxe4 Rae8 {when
Black is very comfortable.}) 14... Qh4 15. h3 Nf6 {QUESTION: White has
centralized all his pieces. What now? --- ANSWER:} 16. Ng5 $1 {The knight
heads for the fabulous outpost on e6.} ({Instead} 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {would ease
Black's defensive task.}) 16... d5 17. Nge6 Bxe6 ({Trying to exploit the pin
down the e-file with} 17... Rfe8 {would be met with} 18. Nf5 $1 Qh5 19. Nfxg7 {
, forking the queen and rook.}) 18. Rxe6 {Again the 'obvious' recapture is not
necessarily the best. White attacks the c6-pawn and sets a well-concealed trap,
} ({whereas} 18. Nxe6 {allows} Rf7 {.}) 18... c5 $2 {EXERCISE: Black's last
