1. -- {The Soviet Revolution: During the 1930s and 40s, the Soviet chess
school started to take over, culminating in Mikhail Botvinnik, the sixth World
Champion, coming to the chess throne in 1948. The Soviets looked to build upon
both the hypermodern and classical ways of thinking. They tended to favour the
classical approach, whilst stressing the importance of taking the initiative
and using active piece play, often at the cost of central pawn weaknesses. A
good example of this is a variation in the Sicilian Defence named after former
world championship candidate Isaac Boleslavsky (1919-1977).} *

