{I would like to end this discussion of the relative weakness of the uncastled
king with a remarkable concept from the current world no.1 Magnus Carlsen.
Despite the game only being a blitz affair, it is well worth a look.} 21. Bxf4
{The position has come about from a sharp variation of the Slav Defence. Black
has seemingly nowhere safe to put his king, but has other trumps such as the
passed pawns on c3 and a5, and the mighty bishop on d5. White has just opened
the f-file and is looking to attack the black king along it. --- QUESTION:
What is Black's best plan? --- ANSWER:} Kd7 $1 {Carlsen evacuates his king
over to the queenside where he is strongest, despite all the heavy pieces
still being on the board. Due to the closed nature of the centre and his
ability to close the queenside, he comfortably has the time to do this.} 22.
Ne1 Kc6 23. Nc2 Bb4 {Keeping the queenside closed, whilst at the same time
preparing an attack down the g-file.} 24. Rf2 Qe7 25. Qh3 Rag8 {The black king
sits perfectly safe on the c6-square and it is the white king that starts to
feel the heat.} 26. Bf1 Rg7 27. Ne3 Kb7 28. Ng4 Nd7 29. Bc1 Kc6 30. Ne3 Nb6 $6
(30... Rhg8 {would have left black in a strong position e.g.} 31. Bxc4 Bxc4 32.
Nxc4 Rg3 {.}) 31. Nxd5 $1 Nxd5 (31... exd5 {allows the white rook to penetrate
on the sixth rank with} 32. Rf6+ Kc7 33. Qf3 {.}) 32. Bxc4 Rhg8 {Black has
misplayed the last few moves (easy to do in blitz!).} 33. Bxd5+ exd5 34. Bxh6
$2 (34. Rf6+ Kc7 35. Ra2 $1 {nicely defends the kingside.}) 34... Rg3 35. Qf5
Qe6 36. Qxe6+ fxe6 37. Bf4 R3g4 38. Be3 {EXERCISE: The dust has settled and we
have an endgame with equal material. How should the world no.1 continue? ---
ANSWER:} Kb5 $1 {The king rejoins the party on the queenside.} 39. h6 Kc4 40.
Kf1 Kd3 41. Rf3 Kc4 42. Rh3 Rf8+ 43. Kg1 Rfg8 44. Kh1 Kb3 {Now it's over. The
black king will assist the promotion of the c-pawn.} 45. Rf1 a4 46. Bd2 Rxd4
47. Bxc3 Bxc3 48. Rc1 Rc4 49. h7 Rh8 50. g4 a3 51. g5 Kb2 52. Rg1 Bxe5 53. Rg2+
Rc2 {. Summary: Castling is not so important in positions with a closed centre,
as we saw in Chapter One. There will be no open files in the middle of the
board for the opponent to attack down. Here Carlsen's king was beautifully
positioned for the endgame that eventually occurred.} 0-1

