met by} 18. Na4 $1 {, removing the rook from its defensive post:} Rc8 ({after} 
18... Bxa4 19. Nf5+ Kg8 20. Qg5+ Ng6 21. Qxg6+ {we can see the power of the
bishop on b3!}) 19. Qg5+ Ng6 20. Nf5+ {is crushing.}) 18. f4 Nc4 19. Bxc4 Rxc4
{Despite being two pawns down, White's attack is in full swing, whereas
Black's is yet to get started. I would take White here any day of the week!}
20. f5 $1 {EXERCISE: Black needs to tread a fine line here. Can you find his
most accurate defensive move?} Rh8 $6 ({ANSWER:} 20... e5 $1 {seems best. This
defends the weak g5-square whilst gaining a tempo on the knight and} 21. fxe6 {
leads nowhere after} fxe6 22. Rxg4 e5 $1 {.}) ({However,} 20... b5 $2 {would
also have been bad as} 21. Rxh5 gxh5 22. Qg5+ Kh7 23. Rh1 {leads to mate.}) 21.
Rxg4 Nf6 22. Rgh4 {White wins control of the all-important h-file with this
move and is now probably winning.} Rxh4 23. Rxh4 Nh5 {EXERCISE: The tempting
24 Rxh5 needs to be calculated. Does it win?} 24. Qg5 {This creates the very
powerful threat of Rxh5.} ({ANSWER: I don't think so.} 24. Rxh5 $2 {seems to
just lead to a perpetual as White has run out of attacking pieces after} gxh5
25. Qg5+ Kh7 26. Qxh5+ Kg7 27. Qg5+ {.}) 24... Qh8 25. fxg6 Rxd4 (25... fxg6
26. Qxe7+ {is curtains.}) 26. Rxh5 f6 27. Qh4 {. The h-file decides matters!} (
27. -- {Summary: With just a couple of inaccurate moves Black got into trouble.
This is one of the reasons why the Sicilian Dragon could be considered risky
from a strategic point of view and why the Yugoslav Attack is considered the
most testing response. The hook on g6 means that Black must be very accurate
