obvious way for White to open things up.}) 14... axb5 15. Bxb5 Ra1+ {Black
drives the white knight back to a passive square.} 16. Nb1 {QUESTION: White
has closed the door for the moment. How can Black keep the attack going?} Bg7
$1 {Williams is very resourceful when it comes to finding ways to attack and a
study of his games will definitely improve your attacking chess! Here he
reroutes the bishop to the diagonal where the king is trapped and threatens ...Bh6 followed by ...e6-e5 when the knight blocks.} 17. e5 $5 {White gives back
the pawn and perhaps believes that he will find some attacking chances of his
own by opening the e-file. However, the Sicilian pawn structures (in this case
a Kan/Taimanov structure with pawns f7-e6-d7) are remarkably resilient and can
stand up to a lot of pressure if necessary.} Bxe5 18. c3 {White gives his king
some air and blocks the long diagonal.} Nf6 (18... Bg7 19. Kc2 Bh6 20. Qe1 {
was also certainly a possibility.}) 19. g3 c4 $6 {A square clearance sacrifice
that seems unnecessary.} ({Following the basic principles of development and
centralization would have been better:} 19... Bb7 20. Rhf1 Nd5 {and Black
stands well.}) 20. Bxc4 Qc5 21. b4 (21. Bxe6 fxe6 22. d4 {is an interesting
tactical shot, but it seems that after} Qb5 23. dxe5 Ne4 $1 24. Qc2 Qxe5 {
Black is still doing well} (24... Nf2 $2 {allows} 25. Nd4 {with a double
attack on the queen and knight.})) 21... Qa7 22. Rhf1 d5 23. Bb3 {The
situation remains tense. As I mentioned above, one of the drawbacks of not
castling is that the rook on h8 can't join in the game and here, because the
g-pawn has gone, castling is unlikely. --- QUESTION: If we forget about the
rook for the moment, can you find another way for Black to get his remaining
pieces going? --- ANSWER:} Ng4 $1 {Threatening ...Ne3 whilst allowing the
dark-squared bishop the opportunity to retreat along the long diagonal.} 24. d4
Bg7 25. h3 $2 ({I never find myself comfortable whilst in a pin and here White
should have taken the opportunity to remove it with} 25. Kb2 {. As it is, the
threat of ...Qa3+ hangs above White's head like the Sword of Damocles.}) 25...
Bh6 26. Nf4 Nf6 27. Qe2 Ne4 {Black's position has certainly improved. 28...
Nxc3 and 28...Nxg3 are threatened and White is now in two pins!} 28. Rf3 $2 {
This loses due to an overloading trick.} ({Relatively best was} 28. Kb2 O-O (
28... Nxg3 29. Qe5 {is unclear.})) 28... Nxg3 29. Qe5 f6 $1 {A very nice move.
Black lures the enemy queen to a vulnerable square.} 30. Qxf6 Qa3+ 31. Kc2 {
EXERCISE: Can you finish White off here?} (31. Kd2 Ne4+ {shows the point of
Black's 29th.}) 31... Ra2+ $1 {(ANSWER)} 32. Bxa2 Qxa2+ 33. Kd3 (33. Kc1 Ne2# {
is mate.}) 33... Ba6+ 34. c4 Bxc4+ ({White resigned as} 34... Bxc4+ 35. Kc3
Ne4# {is mate. A really good fight.}) (34... -- {Summary: White found himself
on the back foot following his mistake on the 12th move, which was castling
into a 'lever' (the ...b7-b5 pawn break) The situation was complicated due to
the position of the black king (and the resulting lack of help from his king's
rook), but White didn't extract himself from the pin along the first rank in
time and ultimately paid the price.}) 0-1

