1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 O-O 5. e4 d6 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 {
White chooses to enter the most principled line, grabbing space and driving
the knight away. He also closes the centre and therefore both sides should
look to play on the flanks.} Ne7 9. Ne1 {EXERCISE: White looks to reroute his
knight to the d3-square, where it will be used to support the c4-c5 advance.
How should Black react here? --- ANSWER:} Nd7 {For a King's Indian player this
idea comes very naturally, though the choice of square is interesting. On d7
the knight obstructs the bishop, but also overprotects the c5-square. The main
point behind the move is to start kingside action though.} 10. Be3 f5 11. f3 f4
12. Bf2 g5 {Black must use his pawns in this instance as the first wave of
attack, as there are many pieces protecting the white king.} 13. b4 Nf6 (13...
h5 {, of course, also suggests itself and is perfectly reasonable.}) (13... b6
$2 {is a move I have seen quite a lot in this sort of position, but it doesn't
help and only weakens the queenside. The point is that after something like}
14. Rc1 Nf6 {the break} 15. c5 {will happen anyway and the light squares will
become a problem for Black. Don't touch pawns on the side of the board where
you are weakest!}) 14. c5 Ng6 {Both sides are playing very naturally,
developing their attacks on the flanks.} 15. cxd6 cxd6 16. Rc1 Rf7 ({QUESTION:
What is wrong with the logical 16...h5 here? --- ANSWER: We must be aware of
what our opponent is up to! White has weakened the queenside and plans to
invade on the c7 square.} 16... h5 $6 17. Nb5 $1 {almost forces a pawn
sacrifice, as} b6 (17... Rf7 18. Nxa7 Bd7 19. a4 g4 {was J.Piket-V.Spasov,
Groningen 1989, when} 20. Nb5 $1 {would have left Black in a perilous state})
18. Nc7 Rb8 19. Nd3 {is really bad for Black. At an opportune moment White
will play Ne6 to exchange off the dangerous light-squared bishop. Instead with
the text move Kasparov covers the sensitive c7-square.}) 17. a4 Bf8 $5 {
QUESTION: This looks rather passive. What is the point? --- ANSWER: Black's
move has two ideas behind it. Firstly, the bishop overprotects another weak
square in the black camp (d6), but more importantly it allows the f7-rook to
swing over on to either the h- or g-files where the white king is situated.} ({
Prior to this game} 17... h5 {had been the main move.}) 18. a5 Bd7 {Again
Black chooses to wait, completing his development before undertaking any
kingside action.} 19. Nb5 {EXERCISE: Multiple choice time! Choose between the
following options: a) 19...a6, taking a time-out to save the a7-pawn and
attack the knight. --- b) 19...Bxb5 to remove the dangerous knight. --- c) 19...b6 to defend the pawn without giving the b6-square away. --- d) 19...g4,
getting on with it.} (19. Kh1 {would have been a useful waiting move, giving
the dark-squared bishop the g1-square.}) 19... g4 $1 {(ANSWER) A difficult one
to judge, but as is often the case in this opening Black must sacrifice on the
queenside or face positional ruin.} (19... a6 $6 {gives away the b6-square:}
20. Nc7 Rc8 21. Bb6 Qe7 22. Rc4 {with all still to play for, though I prefer
White, due to his ability to exchange Black's light-squared bishop at will
with Ne6.}) (19... Bxb5 $2 {would be a positional mistake:} 20. Bxb5 {and
Black can kiss his kingside hopes goodbye as this bishop is really needed to
sacrifice itself on h3 when necessary.}) (19... b6 20. axb6 axb6 21. Rc3 {
followed by doubling on the c-file would be unpleasant.}) 20. Nc7 $6 ({The
tactical point is that} 20. fxg4 {allows} Nxe4 {.}) (20. Nxa7 {was probably
the critical test:} gxf3 (20... g3 {runs into} 21. Bb6) 21. gxf3 (21. Bxf3 Qb8
$1 {'traps' the knight and Black will capture it next move}) 21... Bh3 22. Bb6
Qe7 23. Kh1 $1 Bxf1 24. Bxf1 {with good compensation for the sacrificed
exchange.}) 20... g3 $1 {A pretty pawn chain!} 21. Nxa8 $2 (21. hxg3 fxg3 22.
Bxg3 Nh5 {was the idea, trying to use the dark squares as entry points for the
knights and dark-squared bishop. However, things remain murky after} 23. Bf2
Ngf4 24. Ne6 $1 Nxe6 25. dxe6 Bxe6 26. Bc4 {.}) 21... Nh5 22. Kh1 {ChessBase
gives this as the only move, but I'm not so convinced about this.} ({After} 22.
Bxa7 Qh4 (22... gxh2+ 23. Kxh2 Qh4+ 24. Kg1 Ng3 {looks very dangerous, but
doesn't contain a threat other than to win the exchange; in the meantime White
can get on with things on the queenside and after} 25. Nb6 Nxf1 26. Bxf1 {he
is simply a piece up}) 23. h3 Bxh3 $1 {(showing why we need the light-squared
bishop!)} 24. gxh3 Qxh3 25. Rf2 $1 gxf2+ 26. Kxf2 {it's not clear that Black
has more than a perpetual with} Qg3+ 27. Kf1 Qh3+ 28. Kf2 {.}) 22... gxf2 23.
Rxf2 {EXERCISE: It seems as though the worst is over for Piket, as the white
king sits comfortably behind his pawn shield. --- Kasparov has other ideas
though! What did he play? --- ANSWER:} Ng3+ $1 24. Kg1 $1 ({Acceptance of the
piece sacrifice with} 24. hxg3 {leads to a pretty mate:} fxg3 25. Kg1 Qh4 $1
26. Bc4 Qh2+ 27. Kf1 Nf4 {and ...Qh1 is unstoppable.}) 24... Qxa8 25. Bc4 {
EXERCISE: We have talked about the weakness of the dark squares for White. Can
you see a way to exploit this?} ({Accepting the piece still leads to the same
problem:} 25. hxg3 fxg3 26. Rf1 Nf4 $1 {preventing White from breaking with
f3-f4 again nicely demonstrates how a weak colour complex (the dark squares
here) can be fatal; ...Qd8-h4-h2 can only be avoided at huge material loss.})
25... a6 $1 {(ANSWER) The queen heads for the a7-g1 diagonal.} 26. Qd3 $6 (26.
Nd3 Qa7 27. Nc5 {would have been relatively best.}) 26... Qa7 27. b5 axb5 28.
Bxb5 Nh1 $1 {. An imaginative game by Kasparov, who combined patience in the
early middlegame with a pawnstorm followed by thematic piece sacrifices later
on to try to get at the white king. Piket tried to keep the kingside files
closed, but in the end, although the white king's pawn shield was still intact,
the weakness of his dark squares decided the game.} (28... -- {Summary: 1)
Same side pawnstorms should only be attempted if the centre can be kept closed.
--- 2) Often the pawnstorm on its own will not be enough and piece sacrifices
will be needed to soften the opponent's defences}) 0-1

