1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3 dxc3 4. Bc4 {The Danish gambit was one of the
favourite openings of my youth. White offers two pawns for a pair of
magnificent bishops and a lead in development. The problem was hardly anybody
took the second pawn!} cxb2 5. Bxb2 Qg5 $2 {Oh dear. Black wants all of
White's pawns! A terrible decision by Lasker, who in his prime was regarded as
the strongest player of his generation. What possessed him to play this move I
do not know. --- QUESTION: What should White do about the hanging pawn on g2?}
(5... d5 $1 {is Black's safest option, returning the pawn for development of
his own:} 6. Bxd5 Nf6 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qxd8 Bb4+ $1 9. Qd2 Bxd2+ 10. Nxd2 Re8
11. Ngf3 Nc6 {has been played many times and is approximately equal,} ({but not
} 11... Nxe4 $2 12. Ne5+ Rxe5 13. Bxe5 {, winning an exchange.})) 6. Nf3 $1 {
(ANSWER) Ignore it, of course! White chooses instead to develop another minor
piece with tempo.} Qxg2 7. Rg1 {With tempo on the queen. A simple count says
it all. White has four pieces (two bishops, knight and rook) developed, with
open lines for the queen as well. Black has only developed his queen. Indeed,
it is no a surprise this game doesn't last much longer.} Bb4+ {EXERCISE: Make
a brief comment on the following moves: 8 Ke2, 8 Nbd2, 8 Nc3, and 8 Bc3, and
choose the best. --- ANSWER:} 8. Ke2 $1 {Perhaps it was this move that Black
didn't consider. White keeps maximum lines open, which equals maximum
firepower for his pieces.} (8. Nbd2 Bxd2+ {leaves White in a slightly awkward
situation, as his pawn on f2, knight on f3 and rook on g1 are all slightly
loose.} 9. Ke2 $1 {is still good for him though!}) (8. Nc3 {cannot be
recommended as it blocks the dark-squared bishop in.}) (8. Bc3 $2 {should not
even be seriously considered, swapping off White's mighty bishop far too
cheaply.}) 8... Qh3 9. Bxf7+ {This trick again!} ({Instead} 9. Ng5 {allows}
Qh5+ {.}) 9... Kd8 ({Other moves show the power of open lines:} 9... Kxf7 10.
Ng5+) (9... Ke7 10. Rxg7) ({and} 9... Kf8 10. Bxg7+ {.}) 10. Bxg7 {I bet Black
regretted taking that g2-pawn now. His position is completely hopeless.} Ne7
11. Ng5 $1 Qh4 12. Ne6# {. A pretty picture to finish. White didn't even want
the black rook in the corner!} (12. -- {Summary: I cannot stress enough the
importance (especially to juniors) of the perils of pawn grabbing in the
opening as Lasker found out to his great cost.}) 1-0

