{In 1857 Paul Morphy played a 24 game blindfold match against John William
Schulten, which he won 23-1! The following game shows Morphy at his best,
exploiting his lead in development in aggressive and decisive style.} 1. e4 e5
2. f4 d5 {The Falkbeer Countergambit, an aggressive response to the King's
Gambit.} 3. exd5 ({Of course, not} 3. fxe5 $4 Qh4+ {which is already winning
for Black.}) 3... e4 {Immediately disrupting the development of White's king's
knight.} 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. d3 {QUESTION: What is the best way for Black to
continue here? --- ANSWER:} Bb4 $1 {Developing the bishop, pinning the knight
and preparing to castle.} ({Winning the pawn back with} 5... exd3 6. Bxd3 Nxd5
{allows} 7. Bb5+ c6 8. Qxd5 $1 cxb5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {with a clear advantage to
White.}) 6. Bd2 (6. dxe4 {has scored poorly for White in practice: for example,
} Nxe4 7. Qd4 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 O-O 9. Nf3 Re8 {with good compensation for the
pawn, C.Von Jaenisch-H.Staunton, London 1851.}) 6... e3 $5 {Black sacrifices a
second pawn in order to open the e-file.} 7. Bxe3 O-O 8. Bd2 Bxc3 9. bxc3 (9.
Bxc3 {has also been tried:} Nxd5 10. Qd2 (10. Bd2 $6 Re8+ 11. Be2 Nc6 12. c3 {
, was L.Toth-L.Vass, Hungarian League 1999, and now} ({here} 12. Nf3 Qe7 $1 {
keeps the white king in the cent}) 12... Bf5 {would have given Black a clear
advantage}) 10... Re8+ 11. Be2 {and now the novelty} Bg4 $5 {gives Black good
play, such as after} 12. O-O-O Nxc3 13. bxc3 Be6 14. c4 Qd6 {with pressure on
the queenside.}) 9... Re8+ 10. Be2 {EXERCISE: What's best for Black here? ---
ANSWER:} Bg4 {Again we see how the development of the black pieces come with
tempo. This time there is no direct threat, but the move continues to make the
development of the g1-knight awkward.} 11. c4 $1 {A good response by White,
slowing down Morphy's attack by cementing the centre. --- QUESTION: How can we
continue to play energetically here? --- ANSWER:} c6 $1 {A great move,
preparing the development of the black knight to its most aggressive square
and the introduction of the queen's rook into the game.} 12. dxc6 $2 {Too
co-operative. This mistake was made again almost 150 years later as we will
see in the note to Black's 14th!} (12. h3 {was called for, giving back the
pawn to complete development:} Bxe2 13. Nxe2 cxd5 14. cxd5 Qxd5 15. O-O Nc6 {
with an approximately equal game.}) 12... Nxc6 13. Kf1 {EXERCISE: White unpins
himself and gets ready to exchange the bishops. What should Black do about
this? --- ANSWER:} Rxe2 $1 {Anyone familiar with Morphy's famous game against
the Duke of Brunswick and Count Isouard in 1856 (which we will see again in
Chapter Six) should know this motif!} 14. Nxe2 Nd4 {Here White resigned in P.Vikar-V.Kovar, Havlickur 2005, but Schulten decided to prolong the agony.} 15.
Qb1 Bxe2+ 16. Kf2 Ng4+ 17. Kg1 {EXERCISE: Can you find Morphy's beautiful
finish? --- ANSWER:} Nf3+ $3 18. gxf3 Qd4+ 19. Kg2 Qf2+ 20. Kh3 Qxf3+ ({White
resigned, as} 20... Qxf3+ 21. Kh4 Ne3 22. Rg1 Nf5+ 23. Kg5 Qh5# {is mate.}) (
20... -- {Summary: Power chess from Morphy! Every developing move came with a
threat and just one mistake on move 12 cost White the game.}) 0-1

