{Rudolf Spielmann (1883-1942) was another great attacking chess player, very
much of the romantic school of chess thinking. Another Move by Move author,
Neil McDonald, even wrote a whole book about him! Here we see another great
example of how to exploit a lead in development, even at the cost of material.
} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 {A Grünfeld Defence, played against Mr Grünfeld
himself! Indeed, Ernst Grünfeld popularized this opening at international
level in Vienna 1922, where he defeated Alexander Alekhine with it and hence
it bears his name. It remains one of the most popular and dynamic ways to
counter 1 d4 to this day.} 4. e3 {A solid choice, reinforcing the centre.} Bg7
5. Nf3 O-O 6. Bd2 {A slightly strange developing move, as the bishop doesn't
appear to be any better on d2 than it is on c1.} c6 {Another solid move.} (6...
c5 {is the typical Grünfeld pawn break:} 7. dxc5 Na6 (7... Qa5 {would be the
normal way to win the pawn back, but now we can see the point of the bishop on
d2:} 8. Nxd5 {just wins a pawn}) 8. cxd5 Nxc5 9. Bc4 a6 10. a4 Bf5 11. O-O Rc8
{with decent compensation for the pawn in B.Ivkov-J.Timman, Skopje 1976.}) 7.
Qb3 b6 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Rc1 {It is interesting to see how White keeps his
bishop on f1 for the moment, as it is not clear what the best square for it is.
Is it e2, d3, b5 or even a6? Grünfeld awaits developments before making a
decision. This is why it is generally considered that knights should be
developed before bishops. Their best squares are nearly always c3 and f3 (for
White), and c6 and f6 (for Black).} Bb7 10. Ne5 Nfd7 ({QUESTION: That looks a
bit weird! Why has Black decided to put that knight on d7 and not the
undeveloped one on b8? --- ANSWER:} 10... Nbd7 11. f4 $1 {is White's plan. Now
the e5-knight becomes hard to shift. In fact, Spielmann had reached this
position earlier in the same year. Play continued} Rc8 12. Be2 Nxe5 13. fxe5
Ne4 14. Nxe4 Rxc1+ 15. Bxc1 dxe4 16. Bc4 e6 17. O-O {and a draw was agreed a
few moves later in R.Rey Ardid-R.Spielmann, Sitges 1934.}) ({Instead} 10... Nc6
$6 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Ba6 $1 {controls the c-file and gives White a small
advantage. We can see how useful it was to wait with the bishop in this
variation!}) 11. Nxd7 (11. f4 {still has to be considered. After} Nxe5 ({the
immediate} 11... f6 $2 {allows the shot} 12. Nxg6 $1 hxg6 13. Nxd5 Kh7 (13...
Bxd5 14. Qxd5+ {picks up the rook}) 14. Nc7 {with a winning position for White}
) 12. fxe5 f6 $1 {(trying to blow up the centre whilst the enemy king is still
there)} 13. e6 {the situation looks a little tricky for Black. --- EXERCISE:
The e6-pawn acts as a thorn in Black's side and the knight cannot be developed
to c6 without dropping the d5-pawn. What can we do about this? --- ANSWER:} f5
$1 {(looking to catch the king in the centre)} 14. Be2 f4 $1 15. O-O Nc6 {with
good counterplay for Black as the d4-pawn is a target.}) 11... Nxd7 12. f4 {
White looks to clamp down on the ...e7-e5 break. --- QUESTION: Is there an
effective plan for Black here? --- ANSWER:} e5 $1 {From a practical point of
view this is absolutely the right idea, even though my computer thinks White
can defend against this move. Black looks to rip open central lines as White
is still two moves away from castling.} ({Something lethargic like} 12... Rc8
13. Bd3 Nf6 14. O-O {would give White a small edge. Black has no pawn breaks
and so the middlegame will be more difficult for him to play.}) 13. fxe5 Nxe5
14. dxe5 {EXERCISE: Open lines means maximum firepower for the pieces. What is
better than the automatic recapture 14...Bxe5? --- ANSWER:} d4 $1 {Opening the
a8-h1 diagonal for the bishop and the d-file for the queen.} 15. Nd1 $6 (15.
Ne2 {may have been a better way to defend, trying to force the issue of what
to do with the d4-pawn:} Bxe5 16. exd4 Bxd4 17. Nxd4 Qxd4 {with definite
compensation, although without the dark-squared bishop the situation is not so
dangerous for White.}) 15... Bxe5 16. e4 {White gives back a pawn in order to
try and organize his defences.} Bxe4 17. Nf2 Bd5 {It is clear that the
sacrifice has been successful. Black has a beautiful pair of bishops on the
open board and two pawns for the piece.} 18. Qh3 {White wants to develop his
f1-hishop without dropping the pawn. --- EXERCISE: We must be fast! Our lead
in development isn't going to last long as White looks to get castled. Can you
find a way to keep the king in the centre?} ({Personally I would have
preferred to get my bishop out, even at the cost of g2:} 18. Bc4 Bxg2 19. Rg1
Bb7 {, though Black's position is still for choice here.}) 18... Qe7 {(ANSWER)}
19. Be2 d3 $5 {Very imaginative! Black uses typical pressure along the e-file
to keep the king stuck in the centre.} ({Not} 19... Rfe8 $2 20. O-O {and White
is safe!}) 20. Nxd3 (20. Qxd3 Bxg2 21. Rg1 Bb7 {is similar to the note to
White's 18th, above.}) 20... Rfe8 $1 21. Kf1 $2 {White cracks under pressure,
but this is unsurprising thanks to Spielmann's energetic play.} (21. O-O Bd4+ {
is the main point, when the e2-bishop will fall.}) ({Instead} 21. Qe3 $1 {was
the best defence when one sample line runs} Qh4+ 22. g3 Bxg3+ 23. Qxg3 Qxg3+
24. hxg3 Bxh1 25. Kf2 Bd5 {with all still to play for in the endgame.}) 21...
Bxb2 22. Re1 {White's king is boxed in by his own pieces. --- QUESTION: How
can Black exploit this? --- ANSWER:} Qf6+ $1 23. Nf2 (23. Nf4 Be5 24. Qg3 g5 {
would regain the sacrificed piece with interest}) ({while} 23. Kg1 Bd4+ {is
terminal.}) 23... Bd4 24. Qg3 {EXERCISE: White is completely tied up and Black
can conclude the game. Can you see how?} Re4 $2 ({ANSWER:} 24... Rxe2 $1 {was
the way forward:} 25. Rxe2 (25. Kxe2 Bxf2 26. Qxf2 Bc4+ {wins the white queen})
25... Bc4 {and White is trussed up like a turkey with 26...Re8 coming.}) 25. h4
$2 {White misses his chance to unravel a bit.} (25. Rc1 $1 {, defending c4 and
preparing Bf3, offers good chances to resist.}) 25... Rae8 26. Bb5 Rxe1+ 27.
Bxe1 Re3 {Now it's hopeless for White. The black pieces are just too well
co-ordinated.} 28. Qg5 Rxe1+ $1 29. Kxe1 Qxf2+ 30. Kd1 Bxg2 31. Re1 Bf3+ 32.
Be2 Bc3 33. Bxf3 Qxf3+ 34. Kc2 Bxe1 35. Qd8+ Kg7 {. Summary: A very powerful
attacking game from Spielmann, who recognized with 12...e5! that he could
exploit his small lead in development (in this case the opponent's uncastled
king). The idea of doubling to attack a piece on the e-file (the bishop on e2)
was particularly important to prevent Grünfeld's king from finding safety.} 0-1

