1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 {Delaying the development of the b1-knight is a
little bit annoying for a Grünfeld player.} c6 ({After} 3... Bg7 4. Bg2 d5 (
4... O-O 5. Nc3 {makes ...d5 difficult to play}) 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 {due to
the absence of the knight on c3, Black cannot carry out his typical exchange
followed by ...c7-c5 break. Here} Nb6 7. Ne2 {was a favourite weapon of
Anatoly Karpov.}) 4. Bg2 (4. d5 $5 {is not the most ridiculous move in the
world here, simply to prevent Black's next:} cxd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 {, as in V.Korchnoi-E.Geller, Moscow Candidates 1971.}) 4... d5 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Nc3 Bg7 7.
e3 O-O 8. Nge2 Nc6 9. O-O {EXERCISE: A good time to ask yourself - how do I
most effectively complete my development and where does the bishop on c8 want
to be? --- ANSWER:} b6 {Fischer chooses to put his bishop on a6-f1 diagonal,
where it can't be disturbed.} ({Instead} 9... Bg4 10. h3 {clearly doesn't help
Black}) ({but} 9... Bf5 {is quite logical, although Black needs to be wary of
the typical idea} 10. Qb3 {, attacking both the b7- and d5-pawns. In this
particular case it can be met with} Na5 {.}) 10. b3 {Byrne follows suit.} Ba6
11. Ba3 Re8 12. Qd2 {It is common for the white queen to come to e2, d2 or c2
in the opening to connect the rooks.} e5 {A brave move, which probably left
Robert Byrne a bit taken aback. In exchange for the severely weakened d5-pawn
Black obtains minor piece activity. Such a dynamic approach was very much in
keeping with Fischer's style! For more on this see Chapter One.} 13. dxe5 Nxe5
14. Rfd1 $2 {Very natural. White seeks to place his rooks on their best
squares (d1 and c1), but in doing so gives Black a target for his pieces. ---
QUESTION: What is the drawback of the move Rf1-d1? --- ANSWER: It weakens f2.
The pawns on f2 and g3 now give rise to some tactical opportunities which
Fischer is quick to exploit.} (14. Rad1 {was given as best by Fischer.}) 14...
Nd3 15. Qc2 {White prepares to play Rxd3.} Nxf2 $1 {Highlighting the drawback
to White's 14th move.} 16. Kxf2 Ng4+ 17. Kg1 Nxe3 18. Qd2 {EXERCISE: Fischer's
next move completely surprised Byrne, who was expecting 18...Nxd1. What was it
that he had underestimated? --- ANSWER:} Nxg2 $1 {Very logical! Black gives
himself two bishops on an open board and commendably doesn't take the material
on offer.} 19. Kxg2 d4 20. Nxd4 Bb7+ 21. Kf1 Qd7 {. White resigned due to the
overwhelming weaknesses on the light squares.} (21... -- {Summary: When
developing your rooks, take a good look at the pawns they will no longer be
defending and check there is no easy way for the opponent to get at these
pawns. This is particularly true of the kingside rook as the f2- and f7-pawns
cover some important squares.}) 0-1

