the f7-pawn.} Bd7 {EXERCISE: A difficult position to handle! Which side of the
board should White be playing on and how can he improve his position? ---
ANSWER: The kingside, due to his pawns on e5 and h5.} 13. Nh4 $1 {With his
last move White opens a path for his queen to target the other weak black pawn
on g7.} ({Instead} 13. Be2 $6 {would be a typical case of indecisive
development! The bishop doesn't achieve anything on this square, other than
blocking the white queen.}) ({However,} 13. Rb1 {could be considered.}) 13...
g5 $6 {Black reacts violently, but simply weakens the kingside pawns further -
don't touch your pawns on the side of the board where you are weakest!} (13...
Nf5 {is a better move, as played by one of the leading French experts of
modern times:} 14. Nxf5 exf5 15. g4 $5 fxg4 16. Be2 Nd8 17. Bxg4 Ne6 {with an
unclear game, A.Khalifman-Y.Shulman, Khanty-Mansiysk 2005.}) 14. hxg6 fxg6 15.
