{would also have been bad for Black.}) 16. Nxg6 Nxg6 17. Rxg6 Ne7 {Black seeks
counterplay down the h-file at the cost of another pawn.} 18. Rxh6 Rxh6 19.
Bxh6 Rh8 20. Bg5 {Here we can see the value of White having not moved his
f1-bishop. There is no annoying check on h1!} Ng6 21. Bf6 Rh1 {EXERCISE: How
does White best extract himself from the pin? --- ANSWER:} 22. Kd2 $1 {Calm.
The closed centre provides shelter for the white monarch, whilst he also
defends the sensitive c2-pawn, allowing the queen to move!} Be8 23. Qg4 Bf7 24.
f4 {White is two safe pawns up and the kingside gets ready to roll.} Qd7 25.
Re1 Ne7 26. Bxe7 Qxe7 27. Qg7 a5 28. f5 Kb8 29. Qf6 Qe8 30. Be2 Rxe1 31. Kxe1
Qg8 32. fxe6 Bxe6 33. Kf2 Bf7 34. g4 Be6 35. Kg3 b5 36. g5 Bf7 37. Qb6+ Kc8 38.
