{This interesting game, played by one of my students involves some instructive
pawn breaks. White is graded ECF 141 (converted elo 1778) and Black 115 (elo
1570)} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 d5 4. e3 Bd7 $6 {This is unnecessary. In
general we should try not to develop pieces unless they are going to squares
which improve their activity and thus benefit our position.} ({More common is
something like} 4... c5 {, taking the time to make a pawn break which will
open the position in the future. After} 5. c3 Nc6 6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O {we
reach a roughly balanced position.}) 5. Bd3 c5 6. c3 {EXERCISE: An interesting
moment has arisen. How do you rate the move 6...c4?} c4 $6 {ANSWER: We saw
this move in the previous game in a different structure (with a white pawn on
e5 already). In that case it was good because the bishop had to go back to e2
which allowed Black to thwart the dangerous threat to h7. It's not an easy one
to get to the bottom of, but I don't like the move in this particular position.
The reason being that Black releases the pressure on White's d-pawn. This
makes White's forthcoming pawn break (which we will see in a minute) more
effective.} ({As there was no threat to capture on c5, it would have been
better to finish development with something like} 6... Nc6 7. O-O {and then:}
-- (7... Be7 8. dxc5 {(a typical exchange, gaining a tempo after the bishop
has moved)} Bxc5 9. Nbd2 O-O {with equal chances.}) (7... Nh5 {is quite a
typical move in such positions, trying to grab the bishop-pair, but it doesn't
seem to achieve the aim after} 8. Bg5 Qb6 (8... f6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Nxg5 {is
curtains for Black due to the hanging knight on h5}) 9. b3 h6 10. Bh4 g5 11.
Ne1 $1 {.})) 7. Bc2 Be7 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. Qb1 $6 {An odd-looking move which
doesn't really improve the position of the white queen.} g6 $6 {This is
unnecessary, weakening the dark squares around the king too much. If Black had
wanted to release the knight then 9...h6 would have made more sense. ---
QUESTION: White has two possible pawn breaks in the position, b2-b3 and e3-e4.
Which one should he prepare? --- ANSWER:} 10. e4 {This is the better of the
two, and the effective pawn break that I was referring to earlier.} (10. b3 b5
11. a4 {would be a typical way of trying to break up the strong queenside pawn
chain} -- ({, as} 11... a6 {is impossible due to} 12. axb5 {and Black cannot
recapture with her a-pawn.}) ({. EXERCISE: However, the last two of White's
moves leave the c-pawn weak which Black is able to exploit. How? --- ANSWER:} 
11... b4 $1 12. cxb4 c3 13. Nf1 Bxb4 {leaves Black very comfortably placed.}) (
11... Qa5 $2 12. axb5 Qxc3 13. bxc4 dxc4 14. Bg5 $1 {is devastating.} (14. --))
) 10... Re8 11. e5 Nh5 12. Bg3 $2 {White makes an instructive mistake. One of
the big drawbacks of Black's 9th move (...g7-g6) was that it created a 'hook'
in the position. As we have seen, a hook is a pawn that can be used by the
opponent to lever open a file using a pawn break.} ({In this case after} 12.
Be3 Nc6 13. g4 $1 Ng7 14. h4 $1 {White's attack is already in full swing, as
h4-h5 will open the h-file for the rook using the g6 hook. Here we can see
another drawback of closing the centre too early with 6...c4?!. White is free
to attack on the kingside, even though he hasn't castled. For example, if
Black tries to get some queenside play going with something like} b5 {then
after} 15. h5 b4 16. hxg6 ({much stronger than the greedy} 16. h6 $2 bxc3 17.
bxc3 Qa5 $1 18. hxg7 Qxc3 {when the active black pieces after ...Rb8 and ...Ba3 give good compensation for the piece}) 16... hxg6 17. Bxg6 $1 fxg6 18. Qxg6
{White's attack crashes through.}) 12... Nc6 13. b3 $2 {Perhaps understandably,
White becomes frustrated with his position. It is now much more difficult to
find a constructive plan as his kingside play is hampered by his dark-squared
bishop and his only pawn break now helps Black! --- EXERCISE: White faces some
strategic difficulties after 13 b3?. What should Black play?} ({Instead:} 13.
O-O b5 14. a3 a5 {also leaves Black with good play on the queenside.}) ({The
plan of releasing the bishop with} 13. h4 b5 14. Bh2 {now turns out to be too
slow:} b4 15. g4 Ng7 16. h5 bxc3 17. bxc3 Qa5 {and the white queenside will
collapse.}) 13... b5 {Very natural,} ({but if Zoe had considered the drawbacks
to White's last move a little more carefully she may have found: ANSWER:} 13...
Qa5 $1 14. b4 ({or} 14. bxc4 Qxc3 15. O-O ({while here after} 15. cxd5 Nxd4 16.
Nxd4 Qxd4 {White will be ruing the fact that he hasn't castled already}) 15...
Nxg3 16. hxg3 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Qxd4 {with a clear advantage to Black}) 14... Qa3
15. b5 Nd8 {is terrible for White.}) 14. h3 $2 {White looks to play Bg3-h2,
but just weakens his kingside pawn structure.} Nxg3 15. fxg3 Rb8 $6 (15... Qa5
{is now even stronger.}) 16. b4 a5 17. a3 Ra8 18. O-O {EXERCISE: Black's last
few moves have been very logical, but which of the following moves would you
play here: 18...Ra6, 18...axb4, 18...f6 or 18...a4?} axb4 $6 {As with the
earlier ...c5-c4 move I'm not a massive fan of this one. Maintaining the
tension is better. Black has three squares on the a-file to use for her major
pieces (a6, a7 and a8), whilst White only has two (a1 and a2), so Black should
win control of the file.} ({ANSWER:} 18... Ra6 $1 {is the most natural
continuation. Black wants to double, or in some cases triple her major pieces
on the a-file before releasing the tension.} 19. -- ({. You would have needed
to calculate the consequences of} 19. a4 $6 {before playing the move, however:}
axb4 20. axb5 (20. cxb4 Nxb4 {is a free pawn}) 20... Rxa1 21. Qxa1 Nb8 $1 22.
cxb4 Bxb5 {is clearly better for Black, since the b-pawn is in huge trouble,
as shown by} 23. Rb1 Nc6 24. Qc3 Bxb4 $1 25. Rxb4 Qa5 {.}) ({. Instead} 19. Qe1
{with the idea of abandoning the a-file for some kingside play looks best here:
} Qc7 20. Qe3 Rea8 21. Rac1 axb4 22. axb4 Ra3 23. Nh2 {is still unclear.})) ({
Of the other options,} 18... f6 $4 {allows the shot} 19. Bxg6 hxg6 20. Qxg6+
Kh8 21. Ng5 $1 fxg5 22. Rf7 {which is the end}) ({and} 18... a4 $2 {is
strategically very wrong as Black loses all play on the side of the board on
which she is strongest. It also gives White a free hand to play on the
