{Next we shall see another closed position arising from a French Defence and
see how Nigel Short, one of Britain's greatest ever players, handles the black
side.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 {Just as in my game
against the Abbey students!} 6. a3 {Why are you stopping us on move 6 I hear
you cry! Well, if you search the games of the top-rated players in the world
you will find that this is not considered the most accurate move. The reason
is that the black queen in all likelihood will not go to b6 anymore, but
instead provide increased pressure on the e5-pawn. --- QUESTION: What Black
should play here? --- ANSWER:} f6 {A classic French pawn break!} ({A serious
alternative and in fact the most popular move in the position is} 6... c4 {
which stops the white bishop coming to d3, as well as fixing the weak square
on b3. However, once again Black loses some of the dynamism in his position,
as his only real way of opening lines is then ...f7-f6.} 7. g3 {is now logical
as the white bishop looks for a better diagonal and after} Na5 8. Nbd2 Ne7 9.
Bg2 Nc8 10. O-O Nb6 11. Ne1 Qc7 12. f4 h5 13. Nc2 O-O-O 14. Ne3 f5 {both sides
called it a day due to the lack of effective pawn breaks in Peng Xiaomin-Zhang
Zhong, Beijing 2000.}) 7. Bd3 Qc7 8. O-O O-O-O 9. Qe2 {QUESTION: Black has
made an interesting decision to castle long. What should his plan be now? ---
ANSWER:} h6 {It is interesting to see how Short retains the tension in the
centre. His last move plans ...g7-g5 and a kingside attack.} ({Instead} 9... c4
10. Bc2 h6 {would have allowed an extra option for White in} 11. b3 cxb3 12.
Bxb3 {, with chances for both sides.}) 10. b4 c4 (10... fxe5 {must also have
come into consideration here. Short might have been worried about something
like} 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Bf4 c4 13. Bc2 Bd6 14. dxe5 Bf8 15. Nd2 {with a good
potential outpost on d4 if the knight can reach it.}) 11. Bc2 {QUESTION: Okay,
what now? --- ANSWER: The queenside is closed as there are no pawn breaks
available there, so Black can turn his attention to playing on the kingside.}
f5 {A very interesting decision, which apparently closes the position up. Less
inexperienced players often think that the game is inevitably heading for a
draw in such positions. However, there are still chances to open lines, so
it's actually far too early to say that!} ({The first move that came to my
mind was} 11... g5 {, but there seems to be a problem: White can change the
pawn structure with} 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Re1 Bd6 14. a4 Rde8 15. Ne5 $1 {with
the age old problem of a knight occupying the outpost! White enjoys a decent
game here thanks to the position of the knight and may follow up with b5 and
Ba3 to exchange off the dark-squared bishop.}) 12. Nh4 $6 {Grischuk wants to
shut down the kingside with f2-f4, but doesn't really achieve his aim, as the ...g7-g5 pawn break is still always possible.} (12. h4 {would be another way of
trying to keep the kingside closed. Then:} Be8 $1 {would be a typical
manoeuvre, bringing the bishop to h5 and allowing the queen to join in the
game.} (12... g5 $5 {is the most energetic move and I also like this
suggestion. Perhaps the only problem is that after} 13. hxg5 Be8 {White can
close the h-file with} 14. g6 {. Having said that, after} Bxg6 15. Bf4 Bh5 {I
still like Black's position.})) 12... Be8 13. f4 Be7 14. Nxf5 $6 {Incredible!
White must have felt so uncomfortable about the threat of ...g7-g5 that he
decides to sacrifice a piece. A famous saying in chess is that "the threat is
stronger than the execution", which is usually attributed to Aron Nimzowitsch 
(though the chess historian Edward Winter thinks that the quote could be
earlier than this, from the late 19th century). One of the points is that the
psychological pressure of the threat can cause the opponent to make an
unexpected and in this case sub-optimal reply.} ({After the more natural} 14.
Nf3 {Black can build up with} Bh5 ({if} 14... g5 15. fxg5 hxg5 16. Nxg5 Bh5 17.
Qf2) 15. Be3 Kb8 16. a4 g5 17. Na3 Qd7 {with good play, although of course the
game is far from over.}) 14... exf5 15. Bxf5+ Kb8 16. Qg4 $6 {EXERCISE: Find
an effective way to open lines against the white king.} (16. Bc2 {is better,
since} g5 {can now be met with} 17. f5 {.}) 16... g5 $1 {(ANSWER) Anyway!
Black gives up a pawn, but opens both the g- and h-files in the process.} 17.
fxg5 hxg5 18. Bxg5 Bh5 19. Qg3 Bxg5 20. Qxg5 Nge7 21. Nd2 Rdg8 {Black is
beautifully co-ordinated and the position should be winning for him.} 22. Qe3
Nxf5 23. Rxf5 Qh7 24. Rf6 {EXERCISE: Find the most effective way to clear the
h-file. --- ANSWER:} Be2 {Cheeky.} 25. h3 ({The bishop heads for the d3-square
and is immune since} 25. Qxe2 Qxh2+ 26. Kf1 Qh1+ 27. Kf2 Rxg2+ {wins the queen.
}) 25... Bd3 26. Kh2 Ne7 27. Nf3 Nf5 28. Qf4 Ka8 29. Rg1 Qh5 30. e6 Be4 31. Rf1
Rg3 32. Rxf5 Qxh3+ {. White resigned as it is checkmate next move.} (32... -- {
Summary: A very well-played game from Nigel Short. By retaining the tension
for as long as possible after his ...c5 and ...f6 breaks, Black was able to
shift his king to the queenside before starting his attack. 12...f5 was well
timed and, as is often the case, when White couldn't see a comfortable way to
meet his opponent's threat (the pawn break ...g7-g5), he decided to sacrifice
material unsoundly.}) 0-1

