{Let's start with a classic example of how to play against an isolated pawn
and see if we can play like former World Champion Anatoly Karpov!} 1. c4 e6 2.
Nc3 d5 3. d4 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. Rc1 dxc4 8. e3 c5 9. Bxc4
cxd4 {EXERCISE: This is where White faces his first major decision. Which way
should he recapture? --- ANSWER:} 10. exd4 {White decides to give himself an
isolani. When there are so many pieces still on the board, this weakness is
rarely felt. It is only when the endgame approaches that this pawn may fall.
--- QUESTION: In exchange for the isolated pawn what positional advantages
does White obtain? --- ANSWER: Threefold: 1) Most importantly White enjoys a
slight space advantage. The d4-pawn cramps Black's position by hindering the ...e6-e5 advance. Consequently the power of the c8-bishop is reduced and this
piece will be hard to develop. Black will often have to play ...b6 and ...Bb7,
which can use up valuable time, as well as set up some tactical ideas for
White based on the weak h1-a8 diagonal and the loose knight on c6. --- 2) The
d-pawn gives White some control over c5 and more importantly e5, which is a
valuable central square in the black camp that could be used by a knight in
the future. We will see how useful this can be in the game Hunt-Danielian
later on. --- 3) Finally, the d4-pawn can often be advanced to d5, bringing
the white pieces to life and opening up the central file towards the black
queen.} (10. Nxd4 {would have also been perfectly reasonable, but would have
given Black the freeing ...e5 break whenever he wished. In fact these days
this move is seen more often, perhaps as a result of this game?}) 10... Nc6 11.
O-O Nh5 12. Bxe7 Nxe7 $1 {The classical way to play against an isolated pawn
is to control (and often occupy) the square in front of it. This 'fixes' the
weakness for later attack and prevents the freeing d4-d5 move.} ({EXERCISE: If
instead Black had played} 12... Qxe7 {, which is a positional mistake, can you
see how White should respond? --- ANSWER:} 13. d5 $1 {- if you got this move,
then well done as we haven't discussed this typical central thrust yet, but it
is seen time and time again. White 'cashes in' his isolated pawn to give his
pieces access to the central squares and open files. After} exd5 14. Nxd5 Qd6
15. Re1 {(threatening 16 Ne7+)} Kh8 16. Ne7 Qxd1 17. Rcxd1 {White enjoys a
pleasant advantage due to his more harmonious and active pieces.}) 13. Bb3 Nf6
(13... Nd5 {would be rushing things too much. Black understandably wants to
occupy d5, but here White will simply trade on d5 and Black will be left with
an isolani too! After} 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Ne5 {White would retain a slight
advantage based on his better-placed knight and queen's rook.}) 14. Ne5 Bd7 (
14... b6 {would be another way to attempt to develop the bishop:} 15. Re1 {,
and now not} (15. Qf3 Rb8 16. Rfd1 Bb7 {is okay for Black}) 15... Bb7 $2 {
which allows the typical sacrifice} 16. Nxf7 Rxf7 ({if} 16... Kxf7 17. Bxe6+
Ke8 18. d5 $1 {and d5-d6 cannot be effectively stopped}) 17. Bxe6 Kf8 18. Qe2
Ng6 19. Bxf7 Kxf7 {when White has the better chances due to the exposed nature
of the black king.}) 15. Qe2 Rc8 16. Ne4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Bc6 $1 {Karpov plays
very concretely to restrain and fix the weak d4-pawn. To this end, he is
unconcerned about the 'sacrifice' of ceding his bishop for White's knight.} 18.
Nxc6 Rxc6 19. Rc3 ({QUESTION: If instead White had played} 19. Rxc6 {, which
way would you have recaptured? --- ANSWER:} bxc6 {is best, fixing the
d5-square permanently.} ({Instead} 19... Nxc6 20. d5 exd5 21. Bxd5 {should
still be okay for Black, but I prefer White here with his more active bishop.})
) 19... Qd6 {In the next phase of the game Karpov instructively simply
increases the pressure on the d4-pawn, thus tying White's forces down to its
defence.} 20. g3 Rd8 21. Rd1 Rb6 (21... Qd7 $4 {with the idea of ...Rd6 would
be met by} 22. Ba4 {.}) 22. Qe1 Qd7 (22... Rb4 {would have allowed the
ingenious tactical shot} 23. d5 $1 Nxd5 (23... exd5 24. Re3 Rd7 25. Red3 {and
White has plenty of pressure against the d5-pawn}) 24. Bxd5 exd5 25. Rcd3 d4 ({
or} 25... Rb5 26. a4 Rc5 27. b4) 26. a3 Rxb2 27. Rxd4 Qxd4 28. Rxd4 Rxd4 {and
White should hold.}) 23. Rcd3 Rd6 24. Qe4 Qc6 {QUESTION: To swap or not to
swap? --- ANSWER:} 25. Qf4 {Best.} ({Instead I suppose} 25. Qxc6 $6 {would at
least have left Black with a difficult choice. Due to the lack of pieces on
the board and the pressure down the d-file,} Nxc6 {is the most forcing:} 26. d5
Nb4 27. Rc3 Nxd5 28. Bxd5 Rxd5 (28... exd5 $5) 29. Rxd5 Rxd5 30. Rc7 Rb5 {
leaves Black with all the chances, though the old saying of Dr Tarrasch that
all rook endings are drawn (untrue of course, but they do have a high drawish
tendency) may come into play here!}) 25... Nd5 26. Qd2 Qb6 27. Bxd5 Rxd5 28.
Rb3 Qc6 29. Qc3 {EXERCISE: What did Karpov play here? --- ANSWER:} Qd7 $1 ({
Exchanging queens with} 29... Qxc3 $2 {would be a big mistake as White repairs
his pawn structure just in time as the b7-pawn is hanging. After} 30. bxc3 b6
31. Re1 {White removes himself from the pin.}) 30. f4 {White must prevent ...e6-e5, but this move weakens his king position.} b6 31. Rb4 b5 32. a4 bxa4 33.
Qa3 a5 34. Rxa4 Qb5 35. Rd2 e5 36. fxe5 Rxe5 37. Qa1 $2 {The decisive mistake,
although the white position was very difficult anyway.} ({Perhaps he could
have tried something like} 37. Rf2 Re1+ 38. Kg2 Qc6+ 39. d5 Rxd5 40. Qf3 {.})
37... Qe8 $1 38. dxe5 Rxd2 39. Rxa5 Qc6 40. Ra8+ Kh7 41. Qb1+ g6 42. Qf1 Qc5+
43. Kh1 Qd5+ {. Korchnoi resigned, as ...Rd1 will follow.} (43... -- {Summary:
A highly instructive tussle between two greats of the game. It isn't easy to
put your finger on exactly where Korchnoi went wrong, but Karpov managed to
effectively prevent the d4-pawn from becoming too big an obstacle to the
development of his light-squared bishop. I particularly liked 11...Nh5 in the
early middlegame, exchanging pieces to relieve his space deficiency.}) 0-1

