{Here is another superb example of how to play against an IQP, which I first
came across in Drazen Marovic's book, 'Understanding Pawn Play in Chess'.} 
15... Rad8 {QUESTION: How should White play here? --- ANSWER:} 16. Rd2 {Simple
and strong. White plans to build up pressure on the d5-pawn, again tying Black
down to the defence of his isolated pawn.} (16. Rac1 {(the computer's first
choice!) is also very natural to try and take control of the semi-open c-file.
Play might continue} Rc8 17. h3 Rfd8 18. Bd3 {with a slight edge to White.})
16... Rd7 $6 {The start of a passive plan.} ({Since the d5-pawn is relatively
safe at the moment due to the e6-bishop, I would take the chance to occupy the
c-file and gain some counterplay with} 16... Qc7 17. Rad1 Rc8 {.}) 17. Rad1
Rfd8 18. h3 h6 {EXERCISE: White has improved his position just about as much
as he can without engaging the enemy. How would you continue now? --- ANSWER:}
19. Ne5 $1 {Whilst the c6-knight doesn't directly defend the d5-pawn, it does
defend the square in front of it. Access to this square will allow Botvinnik
to set up a kingside attack.} (19. Nd4 {would also have been good, but was not
as forcing as it doesn't threaten the rook.}) 19... Nxe5 (19... Rc7 {would
allow} 20. Bf3 {, increasing the pressure on d5.}) 20. Qxe5 Qc5 21. Bf3 b6 22.
Qb2 Rc8 23. Qe5 Rcd8 24. Rd4 a5 {EXERCISE: White has amassed all his forces 
(apart from his king!) against the d5-pawn, but Black stands firm. ---
Calculate the consequences of the thematic breakthrough 25 e4.} 25. g4 {Having
presumably seen that 25 e4 didn't promise enough, Botvinnik uses the hook on
h6 to lever open the g-file. Of course, such a move should not be made lightly
as it weakens both White's pawn structure and also his king. However, without
any active pieces other that the queen on c5 Black's counterplay is limited.
White attempts to open a 'second front' on the kingside to create further
weaknesses, while Black's rooks and bishop are passively placed and therefore
will find it difficult to switch their sphere of operations.} ({ANSWER: We saw
this typical motif in Korchnoi-Karpov, but here it isn't enough:} 25. e4 $6
dxe4 26. Qxc5 bxc5 27. Rxd7 Rxd7 28. Rxd7 Bxd7 29. Bxe4 {and a position is
reached where despite Black's two isolated pawns it will be difficult for
White to exploit his advantage, as the pawns can only be attacked by the king
and not the light-squared bishop.}) 25... Qc6 26. g5 hxg5 27. Qxg5 f6 28. Qg6
Bf7 29. Qg3 f5 30. Qg5 Qe6 $6 {EXERCISE: White has certainly made some
progress, though the black position still holds firm. What candidate moves
would you consider in this position?} (30... Rd6 {would have been much better,
trying to use the g-file towards the white king.}) 31. Kh1 {ANSWER: Taking the
king off the g-file is logical, both for king safety and a potential attack.} (
{The move that immediately springs to my mind, along with the text, is} 31. Rf4
{attacking the second weakness. Indeed after} g6 (31... Bg6 32. h4) 32. h4 $1
Kh7 33. Kg2 {White enjoys good prospects of a kingside attack.}) 31... Qe5 32.
Rg1 Rf8 33. Qh6 {The attention has shifted away from the d5-pawn, but note the
superb position of the white rook on d4 in front of the isolani!} Rb8 34. Rh4
Kf8 35. Qh8+ Bg8 {QUESTION: What now for White?} ({Giving up a pawn with} 35...
Ke7 {is a better option, but after} 36. Qxg7 Qxg7 37. Rxg7 Kf6 38. Rhh7 {the
white rooks still put a lot of pressure on the black position.}) 36. Rf4 $1 {
ANSWER: A very classy move, turning the attention away from the h-file to the
weak f5-pawn with the idea of Rg5 or Qh5.} Rbb7 37. Rg5 Rf7 38. Qh5 (38. Bh5
Rf6 39. Bg6 {is even stronger.}) 38... Qa1+ 39. Kg2 g6 40. Qxg6 Bh7 41. Qd6+
Rfe7 42. Qd8+ {. Summary: An instructive game which was very typical of
Botvinnik's style. White built up slowly against the isolated pawn, tying the
black forces down to its defence, before switching the direction of the attack
to the kingside where Black was unable to cope with the opening of a second
front. Note the way that 19 Ne5 gave White important access to and control of
the square in front of the isolani.} 1-0

