} 28. a5 Rc1 {. I think it is easier to go wrong as White here and if we
compare this position to the one before 25 Rxd5 it is clear White has allowed
too much counterplay.}) 25... Rb8 $2 {This weakens the a6-pawn beyond repair.
--- QUESTION: What should White play here?} (25... Qxd4 26. exd4 Rb7 27. a3 (
27. Rxc6 $2 {would be an instructive mistake, giving Black too much activity
in exchange for the pawn after} Rxb4 28. Rcxa6 Rxa6 29. Rxa6 Kf8) 27... Rb6 {
would have been a much better defensive try as the rook isn't pinned down the
c-file any more.}) 26. a3 $1 {ANSWER: Securing his b-pawn and preparing to win
the a6-pawn.} Ra7 $2 {Salwe capitulates, although I can't see a good way of
saving the a6-pawn. --- EXERCISE: As mentioned previously, good co-ordination
often leads to tactical shots. How did White break through here?} ({Indeed,} 
26... Rcb7 27. Bxa6 Qxd4 28. exd4 Rb6 29. Bd3 {would also be good for White.})
27. Rxc6 {(ANSWER) Splat! The c-pawn eventually falls and the game is
technically won.} Qxc6 28. Qxa7 Ra8 29. Qc5 Qb7 30. Kf2 h5 31. Be2 g6 32. Qd6
Qc8 33. Rc5 (33. Rxa6 Rxa6 34. Bxa6 Qc1 {gives Black unnecessary counterplay.})
33... Qb7 34. h4 a5 35. Rc7 Qb8 36. b5 a4 37. b6 Ra5 38. b7 {. Summary:
Rubinstein played a good strategic game against the backward c-pawn, firstly
by immobilizing it, then by gradually exchanging off minor pieces, leaving the
black rooks and queen tied down to its defence. He then used the typical motif
of advancing a pawn to exploit the pin down the c-file and exert further
pressure. This provoked Black into creating another weakness (in this case the
a-pawn), before eventually White picked the c-pawn off.} 1-0

