1. -- {Hanging Pawns: No chess match has ever attracted more media interest or
spawned more books and films than the 1972 World Championship match between
the American Bobby Fischer and the Russian champion Boris Spassky. In the
sixth game of the match Fischer astounded the world by playing 1 c4, as he was
a habitual 1 e4 player, and won a brilliant game. It is a great demonstration
of how to play against the so called 'hanging pawn' formation: two pawns side
by side without any other friendly pawns to defend them. Such a pair can often
become immobile targets for the enemy pieces, in the same way that isolated or
backward pawns can.} *

