1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 {The game has transposed into a
Queen's Gambit.} O-O 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 b6 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {Spassky decides to
exchange off some pieces as he has a slight space disadvantage.} 9. Bxe7 Qxe7
10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Rc1 Be6 12. Qa4 c5 13. Qa3 Rc8 14. Bb5 $5 {EXERCISE: This is
a key moment for Spassky who is trying to avoid being lumbered with a set of
immobile hanging pawns. What should he play?} ({These days} 14. Be2 {is seen
more often.}) 14... a6 {This move has only seen the light of day three times
since the 1970's! After Fischer's powerful display, few players have ventured
to repeat Spassky's choice.} ({ANSWER:} 14... Qb7 $1 {with the idea of ...c5-c4 is the most dynamic move, trying to take advantage of the misplaced
white bishop on b5. The detail is that after} 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Rxc5 Rxc5 17.
Qxc5 Na6 $1 {Black gets good play following} 18. Qc6 ({or} 18. Bxa6 Qxa6 19.
Qa3 Qc4 {when the white king is stuck in the centre, as in J.Timman-E.Geller,
Hilversum 1973}) 18... Qxc6 19. Bxc6 Rb8 $1 {, with the neat point that White
cannot hang on to his pawn with} 20. b3 {as} Rc8 21. Nd4 Nb4 {wins material
thanks to the pin on the bishop to the c1-square. Note that if the pawn was on
b2 then White would have Ba4, defending.}) 15. dxc5 bxc5 {The hanging pawns
have arrived on the scene!} 16. O-O Ra7 (16... Nc6 17. Bxc6 Rxc6 18. Ne5 Rc7
19. Nd3 $1 {was, I imagine, the idea when White looks to probe the hanging
pawns.}) 17. Be2 Nd7 {QUESTION: What should Fischer's plan be?} 18. Nd4 $1 {
ANSWER: White's plan is to apply as much pressure as possible to the hanging
pawn centre. Pawn structure so often dictates how we should play the
middlegame. With his last move White looks to either increase the pressure
with Nb3 or transform the position in his favour (to bishop versus knight)
with Nxe6.} Qf8 {Jan Timman gives this move a question mark in his analysis,} (
{and gives} 18... Nf6 {as better, preventing White's plan in the game. This
encourages} 19. Nb3 Nd7 (19... c4 20. Qxe7 Rxe7 21. Nd4 {gives White a
pleasant pull in the endgame}) {, when I think White can still claim to have a
small edge after} 20. Rc3 {, preparing to double the rooks} (20. Bb5 Nf6 $1 {
is a useful defence.})) 19. Nxe6 fxe6 {QUESTION: So White has traded and
obtained bishop against knight, but what next? --- ANSWER:} 20. e4 $1 {A fine
pawn break, looking to open up diagonals and files, not to mention loosen the
hanging pawns further.} d4 $2 {This move was rightly criticized at the time,
as the pawns become fixed on dark squares. The passed pawn that is created is
irrelevant due to the fact that it is unlikely to be able to advance.} ({Black
must keep the c- and d-pawns together with something like} 20... Nf6 21. exd5
exd5 22. Bf3 {when White is still better due to the pressure on the hanging
pawns.}) 21. f4 Qe7 22. e5 {EXERCISE: White starts to dream of some attacking
chances on the kingside as his pawn crosses the 'halfway line'. --- Can you
find a way to make Black's passed pawns mobile?} Rb8 $6 ({ANSWER:} 22... Nb6 $1
{unpinning the pawn, heading for d5 and preventing White's next move is
Black's best and most active defence. For example, if White carries on with}
23. f5 {then} c4 24. Qa5 d3 {gives Black counterplay.}) 23. Bc4 Kh8 ({Sadly
it's too late now for} 23... Nb6 {, in view of} 24. Qb3 $1 {.}) 24. Qh3 Nf8 25.
b3 a5 {EXERCISE: The position makes for a sad sight for Black whose pieces are
uncoordinated. How should Fischer proceed? --- ANSWER:} 26. f5 $1 {Of course!
This break opens both the a2-g8 diagonal and f-file which far outweighs the
weakening of the e5-pawn.} exf5 27. Rxf5 Nh7 28. Rcf1 {White has a clear
advantage, but is not as yet winning.} ({Over the next few moves Fischer plays
to dominate the h7-knight before advancing his e-pawn, having avoided the
blunder} 28. Rf7 $4 Ng5 {.}) 28... Qd8 29. Qg3 Re7 30. h4 Rbb7 31. e6 Rbc7 32.
Qe5 Qe8 33. a4 Qd8 34. R1f2 Qe8 35. R2f3 Qd8 36. Bd3 Qe8 37. Qe4 {EXERCISE:
Calculate the winning lines for White if Black plays 37...Rxe6 or 37...Nf6.
--- ANSWER:} Nf6 (37... Rxe6 {allows a nice checkmate after} 38. Rf8+ $1 Nxf8
39. Rxf8+ Qxf8 40. Qh7# {.}) 38. Rxf6 $1 gxf6 39. Rxf6 {Actually not too much
calculation was needed. White blows up the kingside and the game is over.} Kg8
40. Bc4 Kh8 41. Qf4 {. Summary: With a set of hanging pawns the key question
is whether or not they can be mobilized. If they can't, as in this game, they
will become a target as the game progresses. The fixing of the pawns on c5 and
d4 allowed Fischer's bishop into the game via c4 and he eventually won due to
a direct kingside assault.} 1-0

