shouldn't promise White any advantage.} Nc6 (5... Ne7 6. Nb5 Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 O-O
{is considered the safest when the outpost on d6 doesn't make itself felt so
much as the black king has been evacuated. For example,} 8. c3 Nbc6 9. f4 cxd4
10. cxd4 Nf5 11. Nf3 a6 12. Nc3 f6 {was okay for Black in H.Nakamura-P.Harikrishna, Oropesa del Mar 2000.}) ({I could have also included countless
games from my youth where my opponents played} 5... cxd4 $6 6. Nb5 Bxd2+ (6...
Bc5 7. Qg4 $1 {is annoying}) 7. Qxd2 Ne7 8. Nd6+ Kf8 9. f4 {with a great
position, similar to the game.}) 6. Nb5 {The point of White's last move. The
knight immediately heads for the d6-square, which is under his control.} Bxd2+
7. Qxd2 cxd4 $6 (7... Nxd4 {still gives White the option of jumping into d6,
but safest for the advantage is} 8. Nxd4 cxd4 9. f4 Ne7 10. Nf3 {.}) 8. f4 {
There's no hurry to give the check: d6 can't be defended and White takes a
move to reinforce his control of the outpost.} Nge7 9. Nd6+ {Is the knight in
an outpost? I would say so, even though the d-file is closed.} Kf8 {White
enjoys a clear advantage due to the knight on d6. His simple strategy should
now be to complete development.} 10. Nf3 f6 $6 {Black understandably wants to
undermine the e5-pawn, but this move has the drawback of reducing the safety
of his king.} ({A knight on such a square cannot be tolerated for long and so} 
10... Nf5 {should probably have been preferred, although White still enjoyed a
good position after} 11. Nxf5 exf5 12. Nxd4 Be6 13. Be2 g6 14. O-O-O {in B.Spassky-C.Garcia Palumbo, German Rapid Cup 1989.}) 11. O-O-O Qa5 12. Qxa5 Nxa5
13. Nxd4 fxe5 14. fxe5 Nec6 {EXERCISE: Black has managed to get the queens off,
but his king remains a big problem. How should White proceed? --- ANSWER:} 15.
Bb5 $1 {A very energetic move! Stoica completes the development of his minor
pieces and prepares to occupy the f-file. He is able to give away his defender
of the outpost square as doing so will open files for his rooks.} Nxe5 (15...
Nd8 16. Nxc8 Rxc8 17. Bd7 Rb8 18. Nxe6+ {wasn't much better for Black in J.Janda-R.Turner, Czech League 2010.}) 16. Rde1 $1 {Not giving Black the time to
reorganize his pieces. Note that the other rook wants to be on the f1 square.}
Nac6 (16... Ke7 {would lose a piece to} 17. Nxc8+ Raxc8 18. Rxe5 {.}) 17. Bxc6
Nxc6 18. Rhf1+ Ke7 {EXERCISE: White has harmoniously centralized all his
pieces. How should he continue? --- ANSWER:} 19. Nxc8+ $1 {Under normal
circumstances this would be a dreadful idea (exchanging the powerful knight
for an undeveloped bishop), but here the white pieces simply invade via e6.}
Raxc8 20. Rxe6+ Kd8 21. Rd6+ Kc7 22. Rxd5 Nd8 $2 ({Black's best chance
probably lay in the rook ending after} 22... Nxd4 23. Rf7+ Kb8 24. Rxd4 Rc7 {
, but this should also be winning for White.}) 23. Re1 Nc6 24. Nxc6 $6 (24.
Ne6+ Kb8 25. Rd7 {looks cleanest.}) 24... Kxc6 25. Rg5 Rc7 26. Re6+ Kd7 27.
Rxg7+ Kxe6 28. Rxc7 {. Black had seen enough and resigned. The outpost handed
to White in the opening was the key factor in deciding the game. --- Weak
squares are created by the advance of pawns. Too many thoughtless pawn moves
weaken the squares around them and this can often result in disaster! Knights
are particularly useful in outposts as we have just seen. The reason for this
is that they need advanced support points in order to be effective due to
their relatively short range of movement, when compared to, say, a bishop or
rook which can influence operations from further away. It is the dream of a
knight to find a central outpost (on the c-, d- ,e- or f-files) in enemy
territory on the fifth, or even better the sixth rank.} 1-0

