{Vassily Smyslov (1921-2010) was the seventh World champion between 1957 and
1958. He had a very clear strategic style of play and was considered to be a
very fine endgame player. Here we see him use a clear and direct plan to
utilize a central outpost.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6
6. Be2 {A classical approach to the Scheveningen Sicilian employed by Black.}
Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Be3 Nc6 {QUESTION: Both sides have developed sensibly so far.
How would you continue as White here? --- ANSWER:} 9. f4 {By far the most
popular move, gaining space on the kingside.} Qc7 10. Qe1 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 e5 {
The typical Sicilian thrust again! In isolation this isn't a mistake...} 12.
Be3 Be6 $6 {...but with the addition of this move it probably is.} ({After
this game the favoured treatment for Black became} 12... exf4 13. Rxf4 Be6 14.
Qg3 Nd7 $1 {. Here we can see that Black aims to employ his knight to the
outpost e5, whilst keeping an eye on d5 with his bishop. The position is about
equal.}) 13. f5 Bc4 {QUESTION: How can White win the battle for the d5-square?}
({Perhaps} 13... Bd7 {should have been considered, looking to reroute the
bishop to c6 to defend the outpost square.}) 14. Bxc4 {(ANSWER)} (14. Bg5 {
leads to some complications based on the weakness of the b2-pawn:} Qb6+ 15. Kh1
Bxe2 16. Qxe2 Qxb2 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Nd5 Rfc8 {gives White compensation for
the sacrificed pawn, but probably no more.}) 14... Qxc4 15. Bg5 $1 {Smyslov
continues in a very logical manner, looking to destroy the defender of our key
outpost square, d5.} Rfe8 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Nd5 {And the knight arrives! It is
worth pointing out that the strength of the outpost increases when the
opponent has no remaining knight or a bishop of the same colour as the outpost
square. On its own the outpost isn't enough to win the game, so the next phase
of the battle sees White gradually improving his position.} Bd8 (17... Qxc2 $2
{runs into} 18. Rf2 $1 (18. Rc1 Qxb2 19. Nc7 Qxa2 {isn't so clear as Black has
plenty of pawns for the exchange}) ({the tempting} 18. Nxf6+ gxf6 {doesn't
seem to lead anywhere either as White doesn't have enough pieces in the attack}
) 18... Qc5 19. Rc1 Qd4 20. Nc7 {, picking up the exchange.}) 18. c3 {
Preventing any counterplay down the c-file for the moment.} b5 19. b3 Qc5+ 20.
Kh1 Rc8 {EXERCISE: How to proceed? Black's position is passive, but he doesn't
have any serious weaknesses, apart from the d5-square!} 21. Rf3 $6 {Another
logical move, looking to swing the rook to the kingside while reinforcing the
c3-pawn.} ({ANSWER: However,} 21. f6 $1 {is stronger though, if you spotted
the pretty idea} gxf6 (21... g6 {simply loses to the typical motif} 22. Qd2 Kh8
23. Qh6 Rg8 24. Rf3 {with the dual threats of Qxh7+ and Rh3}) 22. Rxf6 $1 (22.
Nxf6+ $2 Bxf6 23. Rxf6 Qxc3 {gives Black good counterplay}) 22... Bxf6 23.
Nxf6+ Kg7 (23... Kf8 24. Nd7+ {wins the queen}) 24. Qh4 {when Black is
helpless to defend against the vicious combination of knight and queen: for
instance,} Qxc3 25. Qxh7+ Kf8 (25... Kxf6 26. Rf1+ Ke6 27. Qxf7# {is mate}) 26.
Qg8+ Ke7 27. Nd5+ Kd8 28. Qg5+ Kd7 29. Qf5+ Kc6 30. Nxc3 {.}) 21... Kh8 (21...
f6 {is a really sad move to have to play, but looks best.}) 22. f6 $1 {Smyslov
isn't going to make the same mistake twice! The beast on d5 acts as a superb
aide to the kingside attack.} gxf6 23. Qh4 Rg8 24. Nxf6 {White can finally
afford to exchange off knight for bishop, as the attack is so strong.} Rg7 (
24... Bxf6 25. Qxf6+ Rg7 26. Rg3 Rcg8 27. Rd1 {transposes to the game.}) 25.
Rg3 Bxf6 26. Qxf6 Rcg8 27. Rd1 d5 28. Rxg7 ({Black resigned as he will have to
give up his queen to avoid mate after} 28. Rxg7 Rxg7 29. Rxd5 {.}) (28. -- {
Summary: White managed to win the battle for the weak d5-square thanks to a
careless exchange of light-squared bishops by Rudakovsky. Once the knight was
in place it was used as a support for an attack on the flank. Powerful stuff
from Smyslov.}) 1-0

