1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 {As already mentioned in this
book, Kasparov favoured dynamic openings which promised early imbalances. The
Najdorf was ideal for this during the 80s and 90s, when there wasn't so much
information available on the openings. These days the opening has been pretty
much analysed to death!} a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 (7... Be6 8. O-O Be7 9. f4 Qc7
10. f5 Bc4 11. Bg5 {shows an important difference to the Smyslov game we have
just examined - the black knight can be strengthened by his colleague:} Nbd7
12. a4 O-O 13. Kh1 Rfc8 {, as in L.Oll-G.Kasparov, Moscow Olympiad 1994.}) 8.
Bg5 {White carries out the same plan as before.} Be6 {QUESTION: Should White
take on f6 here? --- ANSWER: Yes! Otherwise Black will again have time to play
...Nbd7 which gives d5 more security.} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qd3 {White continues
to play logically. Here he plans to build up pressure on the weak d6-pawn.} Nc6
11. Nd5 {QUESTION: How should Black react to the arrival of the white knight?}
(11. O-O-O {is definitely a more testing move. In fact during my year out I
reached this position!} Nd4 $6 (11... Qb6 $5 {is a typical way out, giving up
the pawn for play down the d-file:} 12. Qxd6 Be7 13. Nd5 Bxd5 14. Qxd5 O-O 15.
Qd2 Qxf2 {was shortly agreed drawn in V.Anand-V.Topalov, Linares 2000}) 12.
Nxd4 exd4 13. Nd5 Bxd5 14. exd5 O-O 15. Kb1 Re8 16. Qf3 Qa5 17. Bd3 Re5 18. g4
Qxd5 19. Qxd5 Rxd5 20. f4 g6 $4 (20... g5 {is better}) 21. b4 $1 {left my rook
high and dry with nowhere to go in Y.Liou-A.Hunt, Fremont 2012. I feel
slightly better that I am not the only person to make this blunder in the
given position. In fact I can find six other examples of this (with an average
Elo for Black of about 2400!), with White scoring 5½/6!}) 11... Bg5 {ANSWER:
A good move! Black activates his bishop.} ({Others:} 11... Bxd5 12. Qxd5 {is a
bit better for White due to the continued pressure on the d6-pawn.}) (11... Ne7
$2 {would be too early as Black's kingside will be wrecked after} 12. Nxf6+
gxf6 13. O-O-O {with a clear advantage to White.}) 12. O-O Ne7 $1 {And this is
the big plan, getting rid of the knight whilst keeping the bishop-pair.} 13.
Nxe7 (13. c4 Nxd5 14. cxd5 Bd7 {would leave Black feeling happier about his
prospects as the backward pawn on d6 has been 'fixed' by the closure of the
d-file.}) 13... Qxe7 14. Rfd1 Rd8 15. Na5 O-O 16. Nc4 d5 $1 {The second phase
of the plan is complete. Black has removed his backward d-pawn, repaired the
hole on d5 and now stands well due to his pair of bishops.} 17. exd5 (17. Nxe5
{allows the clever move} Bc8 $1 18. Qg3 (18. Qc3 dxe4) 18... Bh4 19. Qf4 g5 20.
Qd2 Qxe5 21. g3 Qxe4 {when Black is a bit better.}) 17... Rxd5 {and Black,
having more than equalized, went on to win in 58 moves.} (17... -- {Summary:
Kasparov demonstrated an effective strategy against the weak d5-square. Note
that he wasn't in a rush to hack the knight off as soon as it landed on d5 -
instead he played around it until the exchange was favourable for him.}) 0-1

