1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. d3 Nc6 4. g3 {A Closed Sicilian - not something we have
encountered yet in this book. Note already that the fianchetto here gives
White holes on f3 and h3.} Nf6 5. Bg2 Bg4 $1 {A provocative development of the
bishop and quite a good way to shake White out of his comfort zone.} 6. Nge2 {
Pretty automatic, but this loosens the weak squares (h3 and f3) a little
further. --- EXERCISE: There are two ways to try and immediately exploit the
holes. What are they?} ({Instead} 6. f3 Bd7 7. Be3 g6 8. Qd2 {would have led
to a different sort of game.}) 6... Nd4 $1 {(ANSWER)} (6... Qd7 {preparing ...Bh3 was the other move I had in mind, though White can simply avoid this with}
7. h3 Bh5 8. O-O {, with a pretty decent position.}) ({Okay, I will also give
you that} 6... Ne5 {hits f3, but the text move is more energetic.}) 7. O-O (7.
h3 {is probably better here.}) 7... Nf3+ 8. Kh1 {QUESTION: How should Najdorf
continue here?} (8. Bxf3 Bxf3 {would, of course, weaken the light squares
terribly.}) 8... h5 {ANSWER: Aggressive and good! Black turns his attention to
an immediate kingside attack.} 9. h3 (9. Be3 h4 10. h3 Qd7 $1 {is terrific for
Black.}) 9... e5 $1 {Fixing the centre, thereby securing his king's safety for
the moment and also preventing the jump of the e2-knight to the useful
f4-square.} 10. Nd5 {White tries to make use of the outpost created.} (10. hxg4
hxg4+ 11. Bh3 Rxh3+ 12. Kg2 Rh2# {would be embarrassing.}) 10... Nxd5 11. exd5
Qd7 12. Nc3 {EXERCISE: White voluntarily walks into a discovered attack! With
a multitude of choices, what did the Polish-born Argentinean Grandmaster
choose to do? --- ANSWER:} Qf5 $1 {Keeping the pressure on.} ({In fact White's
last move was quite clever as the tempting} 12... Nh2 13. hxg4 hxg4 (13... Nxf1
14. Qxf1 hxg4+ 15. Kg1 {at first sight looks promising for Black, but in fact
he simply doesn't have any pieces left to mate White; the fianchettoed bishop
has no opponent, so the open h-file is not so important}) 14. Kg1 Qf5 15. Re1
Nf3+ 16. Kf1 $1 {is good for White.}) 13. Be3 h4 $1 {Preparing to soften up
the weak h3-pawn by opening the h-file.} 14. Ne4 Be7 {There is no rush. Black
finishes his minor piece development.} ({After the hasty} 14... hxg3 15. fxg3
Rxh3+ 16. Bxh3 Qh5 17. Ng5 $1 {White defends.}) 15. c4 {EXERCISE: Can you find
a beautiful way to finish White off? --- ANSWER:} hxg3 16. fxg3 Rxh3+ 17. Bxh3
Qh5 $1 18. Qa4+ (18. Nf2 {blocks the pressure on the f3-knight and thus} Bxh3 {
just wins.}) 18... Kf8 19. Rxf3 Qxh3+ ({White resigned as he will lose his
queen after} 19... Qxh3+ 20. Kg1 Bxf3 21. Qc2 Qh1+ 22. Kf2 Qg2+ 23. Ke1 Qxc2 {.
}) (19... -- {Summary: A tremendous game by Najdorf, who systematically
exploited the holes on f3 and later h3 to get at the white king.}) 0-1

