{The white player in the next game is actually one of my sister's students,
but I'm sure she won't mind me analysing this game as her pupil won!} 1. e4 e5
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 {The Berlin Defence which we first came across in
Chapter One.} 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Nxe5 Be7 8. d4 Be6 9. Bf4
O-O 10. Nd2 Nf5 11. Ndf3 {The e5-knight is not on an outpost due to the
potential attack from the black f-pawn. However, it is still well placed, as
any future ...f7-f6 attack will create a hole on e6.} c5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Ng5
$1 {White uses the chance to apply pressure to the e6-bishop.} Bd5 $6 ({I
think Black needed to accept the ending after} 13... Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Rfe8 15.
Nxe6 Rxe6 {. Being slightly higher-graded, it could be that he wanted to win
at all costs.}) 14. c4 Be6 15. Qh5 h6 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Rad1 Qe8 18. Qg4 {
EXERCISE: What do you make of the move 18...h5, gaining a tempo on the queen?}
h5 $2 {ANSWER: Black wants to free the d4-square for his knight by shifting
the queen off the g-file, but from a positional point of view this is
definitely wrong as it weakens the g5-square. So what you may ask? Well, g5 is
important as a white bishop on that square makes fighting for the d-file with ...Rd8 very difficult. Now Black has big holes on e5, g5 and g6.} (18... Rd8 {
would have been better.}) 19. Qh3 Nd4 {So the knight arrives on d4, but it is
not secure as the defender (the bishop on c5) can be removed quite easily. ---
EXERCISE: Can you see a way to eliminate the irritating black knight on d4?} (
19... Bd4 $1 {would have made more sense as the defensive knight on f5 is the
more stable minor piece.}) 20. Be3 {Now the battle rages over the d4-square.} (
{ANSWER:} 20. Nd3 $1 {straightaway would have been even stronger.}) 20... Rd8
21. Nd3 $1 Bb6 {QUESTION: What's best for White here?} (21... b6 22. Nxc5 bxc5
{would leave Black a pawn down in the ending after} 23. Bxd4 Rxd4 24. Rxd4 cxd4
25. Qxe6+ Qxe6 26. Rxe6 {.}) 22. c5 ({ANSWER: Exploiting the weak square
immediately with} 22. Bg5 $1 Rd7 23. c5 {would have been best.}) 22... Nc2 23.
Bg5 Nxe1 24. Bxd8 Nf3+ $2 {This was a rapidplay game and we can only assume
that both players were short of time.} ({Instead} 24... Nxd3 25. Qxd3 Bxc5 {
leaves Black a pawn up.}) 25. gxf3 Qxd8 26. Qxe6+ {Now White is winning easily.
} Kh8 27. cxb6 Qg5+ 28. Kh1 Rxf3 29. Qe8+ Kh7 30. Qe4+ {. Summary: An
interesting fight for the central squares. The innocuous-looking 18...h5?
actually turned out to be a major mistake, as it weakened a crucial square
from which White's bishop could then control the d-file.} 1-0

