{David Bronstein was one of the strongest-ever players never to become World
Champion. I was lucky enough to play him when I was 13 and he taught me a
strategic lesson about holes!} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3
a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nf3 {A more positional approach to the Najdorf.} Qc7 {Designed
to prevent the bishop coming to c4.} (7... Be7 8. Bc4 O-O 9. O-O Be6 {is a
more popular way of fighting for the d5-square.}) 8. a4 b6 9. Bg5 Nbd7 {
EXERCISE: This move was forced in order to retain some control of d5. Can you
now, though, find a way for White to increase his control over this crucial
square? --- ANSWER:} 10. Nd2 $1 {Preparing Bf1-c4 whilst reinforcing the
e4-pawn.} Bb7 11. Bc4 Be7 12. Qe2 {I've landed in one of those passive Najdorf
positions which is miserable for Black to play. The ...b5 and ...d5 breaks
have been prevented and White can slowly improve his position. It is no
surprise that White has scored very well from here in the Mega Database 2012.}
O-O 13. O-O h6 14. Bh4 ({Of course Bronstein doesn't want to release the
tension with} 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 {.}) 14... Qc8 $2 {EXERCISE: Can you figure out
the idea behind the strange-looking text move? Then I want you to find a plan
for White to improve his control of the d5-square.} ({Something extreme like} 
14... g5 15. Bg3 Nc5 $1 {was called for. Black at least fights for some
squares of his own. After} 16. f3 Ne6 17. Bxe6 fxe6 {he was okay in R.Hübner-J.Hjartarson, Tilburg 1988.}) 15. Rfd1 Bc6 {ANSWER: This was my 'brilliant' idea
- to try and increase the pressure on e4 with ...Qb7 whilst protecting the
a6-pawn. Unfortunately it's just too slow.} 16. Nf1 $1 {This is the main idea
behind White's last. The knight heads for e3.} Qb7 17. Ne3 Rfe8 {QUESTION: How
should White continue here?} ({There was no time for} 17... g5 {due to} 18. Nf5
{.}) 18. Nf5 $1 {ANSWER: The other way! One of the dream squares for a knight
is f5, from where it eyes up the g7-h6 pawn complex and also the weakness on
d6. Black's position now collapses like a house of cards.} (18. Ncd5 Bxd5 19.
Nxd5 {would also have been strong, but I like the text more as it gets nearer
the king.}) 18... Bf8 19. Rxd6 {Splat!} Qc7 (19... Bxd6 20. Nxd6 Qc7 21. Bxf7+
Kh7 22. Nxe8 {is also a disaster.}) 20. Bxf7+ (20. Bxf7+ Kxf7 21. Qc4+ Kg6 22.
Rxc6 {is the end.}) (20. -- {Summary: The final white position is a picture of
harmony. The knight on f5 is truly a monster. A model strategic game against
the Najdorf in which Bronstein methodically increased his control over the
d5-square so Black couldn't break there. The game was then decided by an
invasion on another weak square, f5.}) 1-0

