20... Ng6 {One of the best examples of a weak colour complex can arise from
the French Winawer. In this position a simple count tells us that five of the
six black pawns are on light squares. Therefore Black is vulnerable on the
dark squares as the pawns are not controlling them. This is made worse by the
fact there is no dark-squared bishop present to control the dark squares and
doubly worse by the presence of White's dark-squared bishop. Being a piece for
two pawns up also helps!} 21. Rg1 Rg8 ({White was threatening} 21... -- 22.
Rxg6 fxg6 23. Qxh8+ {.}) 22. Bb4 $1 {Renewing the threat as mate will be
threatened on e7.} Qd7 23. Nf4 Qd8 {EXERCISE: Black desperately needs the
queens off to survive. How should White continue? --- ANSWER:} 24. Bb5+ Bd7 25.
Bxd7+ Qxd7 (25... Kxd7 26. Qxf7+ Kc8 27. Qxe6+ {is totally over.}) 26. Nxg6 a5
27. Ne5 Rxg1+ 28. Kf2 {. The game is decided as 29 Qh8+ and the black queen
are both threatened. --- Summary: This snippet shows us that it is risky to
put a lot of your pawns on one colour of square due to the resulting creation
of a weak colour complex. This is magnified if an opponent's bishop or queen 
(or both) is still present.} 1-0

