{Here is another good example of the exploitation of a weak colour complex,
taken from last year's British Championship. This one is a little less obvious,
as both sides lose their dark-squared bishop which would otherwise dominate
the weakened dark squares.} 1. d4 d6 2. e4 g6 3. Be3 Bg7 4. Nc3 c6 5. Qd2 {A
pretty standard and logical set-up. White looks to discourage ...Nf6, as he
will then exchange the dark-squared bishops with Be3-h6.} Nd7 6. O-O-O b5 7. e5
$5 {A very aggressive move! White sinks the g8-knight for the moment. ---
QUESTION: How should Black respond to this bold thrust? --- ANSWER:} d5 {Black
chooses to close the centre.} (7... dxe5 8. d5 (8. dxe5 $5 {is an interesting
novelty:} Bxe5 9. Nf3 Bg7 10. Ne4 Ngf6 11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. Bh6 {with decent
compensation for the pawn}) 8... Bb7 9. dxc6 Bxc6 10. Bxb5 Bxb5 11. Nxb5 {was
slightly better for White in L.Mista-P.Vavra, Czech League 1999.}) 8. Bd3 {I
guess this is designed so that after a ...b5-b4 push, the knight can go back
to e2 without blocking the bishop's defence of c4.} Nb6 9. h4 h5 10. b3 e6 {
With all the black pawns on light squares, it is desirable for White to try
and get the dark-squared bishops exchanged.} 11. f3 ({Something like} 11. Bg5
Qc7 12. Nce2 {also suggests itself, removing the target for the black pawns on
the queenside.}) 11... Nh6 $6 {I don't like this move. f5 is normally a good
square for the knight, but here it can easily be attacked (with g2-g4), and
perhaps more importantly it weakens the sensitive f6-square.} ({Getting on
with it on the queenside with} 11... a5 12. Nh3 a4 {would have made more sense.
}) 12. Bg5 Qc7 13. Qf4 ({QUESTION: White could have immediately exchanged the
bishops with} 13. Bf6 Bxf6 14. exf6 {. What do you make of this? --- ANSWER: I
don't like it. Remember weak squares (such as f6 in this case) like to be
occupied by pieces not pawns, as Dr Tarrasch said. In fact here the f6-pawn
simply becomes a target:} Ng8 15. Qg5 Qd8 {with an acceptable position for
Black.}) 13... b4 14. Bf6 $1 {There is no need to hang about! The threat to
the bishop forces the next sequence of moves.} Bxf6 15. Qxf6 Rf8 16. Nce2 c5 $2
{Looking to open the c-file, but giving away important squares in the process.}
17. dxc5 Qxc5 18. Nd4 $1 {A highly desirable square for the white knight.} Nf5
{EXERCISE: Which way would you take on f5: with the knight or bishop?} ({Of
course it can't be taken:} 18... Qxd4 $4 19. Bb5+ Bd7 20. Rxd4 {wins the queen.
}) 19. Bxf5 $1 {ANSWER: The correct decision. The bishop is relatively
ineffective as the black pawns are all on light squares.} gxf5 20. Nge2 {Now
White has a target for his pieces on h5.} Nd7 21. Qg7 Ba6 22. Nf4 Qc3 23. Kb1
Qe3 $2 {QUESTION: What's the strongest continuation here for White?} ({I think
I would have castled here and given the pawn for free, though Black's position
is still desperate as the White h-pawn is very fast:} 23... O-O-O 24. Nxh5 Qe3
25. Rhe1 {with a virtually winning advantage.}) 24. Qg5 $6 ({ANSWER: After} 24.
Nxd5 $1 exd5 25. Rhe1 Qc3 26. e6 $1 {the black position collapses.}) (24. Rhe1
Qxf4 25. g3 $1 {is also quite pretty.}) 24... Qxe5 25. Nxh5 Rh8 26. Rhe1 Qd6
27. Nxf5 {. Summary: Despite the closed nature of the position out of the
opening, White played consistently to exchange off Black's defender of the
dark squares, before Black committed an error in opening up the middle of the
board.} 1-0

