1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. O-O O-O 6. d4 Bb6 7. Bg5 h6 8. Bh4
d6 9. Qd3 g5 $5 {The start of an ambitious plan.} 10. Bg3 ({Of course Black's
last move could not have been undertaken without serious analysis of the
consequences of} 10. Nxg5 hxg5 11. Bxg5 {, but it seems that he is doing well
after} Kg7 12. f4 (12. Qg3 {loses to} Nxe4) 12... exd4 $1 (12... Qd7 $2 13.
fxe5 Nh7 14. Bf6+ {was winning for White in So.Polgar-R.Bayon Fernandez,
Oviedo (rapid) 1993}) 13. Kh1 Rh8 {.}) 10... Nh5 11. Bxc6 {Perhaps if White
sees what is coming, he might keep hold of his light-squared bishop.} (11. Na3
exd4 12. cxd4 f5 $5 {was a bold decision taken in F.Caruana-P.H.Nielsen,
Amsterdam 2008.}) 11... bxc6 12. Nbd2 a5 13. dxe5 $6 {Opening the position for
the pair of bishops can only be justified if White can win the e5-pawn.} dxe5
14. Qe2 (14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Bxe5 g4 {is the tactical point, so I'm not really
sure why I took on e5.}) 14... Ba6 15. c4 f6 $1 {Without White's light-squared
bishop this strategy is completely justified. The bishop on g3 is completely
dead and Black stands better.} 16. Rfd1 Qe7 17. Ne1 {EXERCISE: White tries to
plug the gaps in his position. What should Black do about the threat to his
h5-knight? --- ANSWER:} Ng7 {The knight heads for the juicy d4-square.} ({
Instead} 17... Nxg3 $2 {would go completely against the dark-square strategy
on the kingside to restrict the enemy bishop}) ({whilst} 17... Nf4 18. Bxf4
exf4 {leaves an interesting material balance (two bishops against two knights),
with an unclear position.}) 18. Nc2 Ne6 19. Nf1 {White looks to get to the
weak square on f5. --- QUESTION: Is there a good way to prevent this plan? ---
ANSWER:} Qh7 $1 {A very good move. Adams uses the pressure on the e4-pawn to
restrict the f1-knight whilst also supporting a future kingside pawn push.} 20.
b3 {I play to block out the a6-bishop. The problem is that it can come back
into the game via c8 whilst my bishop remains stuck.} Rad8 $6 {Mickey
criticized this move after the game and unsurprisingly he seems to have been
right.} (20... Nc5 $1 21. Nd2 Rad8 {would have kept the pressure firmly on, as
the rooks can't be traded and the knight eyes up another hole on d3.}) 21. Kh1
{Planning the release of my bishop with f2-f3, but perhaps this should have
been played two or three moves earlier.} h5 {EXERCISE: It's multiple choice
time! How should White deal with the threat of ...h5-h4: with 22 h4, 22 h3 or
22 f3? --- ANSWER:} 22. h4 {A good decision!} ({Instead:} 22. h3 Bc8 {makes it
awkward for White to play his main plan of f2-f3, as this would then
compromise his kingside dark squares significantly.}) (22. f3 $2 {would be a
serious mistake as it gives Black a dream square for his knight on f4! Then} h4
23. Rxd8 (23. Bf2 Nf4 24. Qe1 h3 $1 {is horrific}) 23... Rxd8 24. Be1 Nf4 {is
disgusting for White.}) 22... g4 23. f3 gxf3 24. gxf3 Kh8 25. Nfe3 {White has
managed to keep himself afloat and his knight now eyes up the weak f5-square.}
Nd4 26. Nxd4 Bxd4 27. Rac1 Rg8 28. Bf2 {I must admit I was feeling much
happier about my position here.} c5 {EXERCISE: Black cements his bishop on d4,
but also gives away the d5-square. What is the correct strategy for White here?
} (28... Bc8 29. Rg1 Be6 {was probably a touch better.}) 29. Rg1 {ANSWER: Get
the rooks off! Due to the exposed nature of the white king, it is important to
get some major pieces exchanged. Notice also how Black's weaker pawn structure
could play a part in any ending.} Bc8 30. Rxg8+ Rxg8 31. Rg1 Be6 32. Rxg8+ Kxg8
{Here Mickey offered a draw. The tournament situation was such that this
result would almost certainly guarantee him first prize, whilst I was happy as
I had made my second GM norm just by playing him! I remember GM Chris Ward,
who was commentating at the time, saying how surprised he was by the draw
offer. In reality I think White has no problems any more as long as he keeps
an eye on his king, though perhaps it is still slightly easier to play as
Black.} ({After} 32... Kxg8 33. Be1 a4 34. bxa4 Qd7 35. a5 Qa4 {there is still
some chess to be played.}) (32... Kxg8 {. Summary: Thanks to good opening
preparation Black managed to carry out a plan of restriction against the
dark-squared bishop which left White in some strategic difficulties. This was
in part due to my early decision to give up my light-squared bishop. From a
defensive perspective it was important to recognize that this also left some
squares weak in the black camp (f5 and d5), and White needed to react
accordingly in order to gain counterplay. In the end I managed to neutralize
the pressure in the nick of time by exchanging off the heavy pieces.}) 1/2-1/2

