{Keeping an Eye on Weak Squares:} 1. e4 e6 {QUESTION: What's this? Something
other than the Sicilian? --- ANSWER: In fact this was only the second time I
had played the French in a rated game. It's sometimes handy to be so one
dimensional for surprise value!} 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 {The Two Knights Variation
is a relatively uncommon but very playable way to meet the French.} Nf6 4. e5
Nfd7 5. d4 c5 6. dxc5 Nc6 7. Bf4 Nxc5 $5 ({This is less common than} 7... Bxc5
{, but I had spotted that my opponent played in a slightly unusual way against
this line.}) 8. Bd3 Be7 {There is no need to rush to take off the d3-bishop as
it doesn't have any better squares.} 9. O-O $6 g5 $1 {A violent reaction, but
also quite a good one. Black will castle queenside.} 10. Bg3 h5 {Targeting the
dark-squared bishop immediately. Due to the closed nature of the centre Black
can get away with such a strategy.} 11. h3 Nxd3 12. Qxd3 Qb6 13. Nb5 {White
prepares to try and exchange off the e7-bishop and then looks to exploit the
resulting weakened dark squares. --- QUESTION: How should Black respond? ---
ANSWER:} g4 $1 {This disrupts White's strategy and prevents the other white
knight jumping to e5,} ({unlike something like} 13... Bd7 14. Nd6+ Bxd6 15.
exd6 O-O-O 16. Ne5 {.}) 14. hxg4 hxg4 15. Nfd4 $6 Bd7 {Black doesn't fear the
check on d6 and completes his development.} 16. Nxc6 Bxc6 17. Nd6+ Bxd6 18.
exd6 {EXERCISE: Black clearly has the initiative, but a pure opposite-coloured
bishop middlegame has been reached, which might become very double-edged. What
do you make of 18...Bb5?} Rh5 ({ANSWER:} 18... Bb5 {wins material, but at some
cost to Black's king after} 19. c4 $1 {(which I had missed initially)} Bxc4 20.
Qc3 Rh7 21. Rfc1 {, although Black should still be better after} Kd7 $1 {. The
text move is designed to fight for control of the e5-square.}) 19. Rfe1 {
EXERCISE: Try to calculate the complications arising after 19...Qxb2. Also,
are there any good alternatives?} Kd7 $1 {ANSWER: From a practical point of
view I am quite happy I played this. It prevents the white bishop from coming
to life and prepares the transfer of the last black piece into the game.} ({
Just as I was about to play} 19... Qxb2 $2 20. -- ({, I noticed} 20. Rxe6+ fxe6
21. Qg6+ {which looks very scary and highlights some of the dangers of
opposite-coloured bishops in the middlegame. White is a whole rook down, but
Black has to tread carefully:} Kf8 {the only move I calculated,} ({but} 21...
Kd8 22. Re1 Qh8 $1 {is actually winning}) 22. Qxh5 (22. Re1 Qh8 {wins due to
the threat of mate on h1}) 22... Qxa1+ 23. Kh2 Be8 $1 {(an important defensive
resource)} 24. Qh6+ Qg7 25. Qxe6 {. I actually got this far in my calculations,
but chickened out in the end as I didn't trust myself.}) ({. What I had missed
in the midst of all of this was} 20. Be5 $3 Qb5 (20... Rxe5 $2 21. Reb1 {is a
crafty way of trapping the black queen}) 21. Qd4 {when White retains a decent
bishop on e5 as compensation for the pawn.})) 20. Be5 {QUESTION: How should
Black continue his initiative?} Rg8 {ANSWER: This move is very logical,
looking to come up and over to h6, but the direct transfer of the queen
appears to be stronger.} ({Indeed,} 20... Qd8 $1 {would have been better. After
} 21. Kf1 (21. Bg3 Qf6 {would be a better square for the black queen}) 21...
Qh4 {Black has a very strong attack.}) 21. Qb3 $6 {This just encourages Black
to execute his plan.} Qd8 22. Bg3 Rgh8 23. Kf1 {EXERCISE: There are lots of
tempting options for Black in this position. Make a list of them before
deciding what you would you do here. --- ANSWER:} d4 {The bishop is finally
brought to life.} ({Alternatively:} 23... Qa5 $1 {is perhaps the strongest
move, looking to invade via d2 while preparing a check on the a6-f1 diagonal.})
(23... Qf6 {also springs to mind.}) 24. a4 Qa5 25. Qc4 $2 {An unfortunate
blunder after White had put up stubborn resistance for the last few moves.} (
25. Ke2 {is relatively best, although Black is just a pawn up with an attack
after} Bxg2 {.}) 25... Qd2 ({After} 25... Qd2 {,} 26. -- Rh1# {cannot be
sensibly stopped so White resigned.}) (25... -- {Summary: Here Black was
successful in defending his weak dark-square colour complex by blockading the
pawn on d6. This helped keep control of the position without allowing the
opponent unnecessary counterplay. Opposite-coloured bishop middlegames are
particularly sharp and a restrictive strategy against the enemy bishop can
often prove important.}) 0-1

