1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3
d6 9. h3 Na5 {The Chigorin variation of the Ruy Lopez is one of the most
studied and famous opening variations of them all! Black misplaces his knight
temporarily in order to drive the enemy bishop away and prepares to gain space
on the queenside.} 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 {Retaining the tension.} 12. Nbd2 Bd7
13. d5 {White closes the centre before Black has a chance to gain counterplay
down the c-file. --- EXERCISE: Identify Black's worst-placed piece and find a
way to improve it.} (13. Nf1 cxd4 14. cxd4 Rac8 15. Ne3 Nc6 {is another
popular line.}) 13... c4 $1 {(ANSWER) --- QUESTION: What was the piece? ---
ANSWER: The knight on a5! Black seeks to reroute this guy to c5. It is rare
for one side to be able to tolerate a knight on the edge of the board for too
long. I am sure you know the saying "a knight on the rim is dim", due to its
lack of mobility. --- The current position is closed and therefore there is
more time for the knight manoeuvre to be carried out. As there are no obvious
pawn breaks or open files available to Black it wouldn't have made a lot of
sense to develop the rooks to the centre either. It is in such closed
positions that knights truly find their feet!} ({The immediate} 13... Nb7 {
would give White an extra preventative option of} 14. b3 c4 15. b4 $5 {,
stopping the knight on b7 from rejoining the game.}) 14. Nf1 {White also looks
to improve his knight, heading for that dream square on f5.} Nb7 15. Ng3 Nc5 {
QUESTION:} 16. Nh2 {EXERCISE: White's knight manoeuvres are quite common in
the Ruy Lopez. He looks to increase his control over f5. Suggest a plan for
Black!} ({In order to remove the knight White would have to weaken his
queenside pawns a bit:} 16. b4 cxb3 17. axb3 Rfc8 18. Bd2 a5 {and Black was
comfortable in V.Lepsakov-Y.Balashov, Ishevsk 2010.}) ({Instead} 16. Nf5 $6 {
would be wrong, as the white d-pawn would become very weak after} Bxf5 17. exf5
Qb7 {. We want a piece (knight) on f5, not a pawn. Remember what was said in
the chapter on outposts?}) ({Neither does} 16. Nh4 {really help as after} g6 {
White will lose more time getting the knight back into play.}) 16... a5 $1 {
(ANSWER) With all his pieces harmoniously placed Black starts to advance on
the queenside where he is strongest.} 17. Qf3 b4 18. Nf5 Bxf5 19. Qxf5 Rfb8 {
Tseshkovsky isn't afraid to leave his kingside, as he correctly judges that
there will be no way through for White.} (19... bxc3 20. bxc3 Nd3 {also
suggests itself, but Black shows more restraint in the game.}) 20. Qf3 Nfd7 {
Again rerouting an inactive piece over to the queenside.} 21. Nf1 {QUESTION:
What is Black's worst piece here and how would you improve it?} b3 ({ANSWER:} 
21... Qd8 $1 {prepares the exchange of Black's poor dark-squared bishop with ...Bg5. Exchanging off a bad piece is usually just as effective as improving it.}
) 22. axb3 cxb3 23. Bd1 a4 24. Rb1 $6 (24. Ra3 {would have been better than
the text move. It seems a bit strange to use a rook to block a pawn charge,
