{Tigran Vartanovich Petrosian (1929-1984) was World Champion from 1963 to 1969.
His style of play was generally pretty cautious, but Petrosian was the master
of prophylaxis and positional play and almost impossible to beat. Here Bobby
Fischer is on the back foot for a change!} 14... Bg7 {Black has been left in
an unpleasant position in a King's Indian Defence, thanks to a mistake on the
13th move. His pawn structure on the kingside is split and both his
light-squared bishop and knight lack good squares. --- QUESTION: How does
White go about improving his position here? --- ANSWER:} 15. Be3 Bd7 16. Bd4 $1
{Petrosian employs the strategy of exchanging off his opponent's best piece,
the bishop on g7.} Ng6 17. Re1 Rf7 $6 (17... Bxd4+ 18. Qxd4 h5 $1 {was Black's
best chance to find some play.}) 18. Bf3 $1 {Now he won't get that chance
again!} Qf8 19. Kf2 Re8 20. Rxe8 Qxe8 21. Bxg7 Rxg7 {EXERCISE: Can you find a
way to improve a piece that is not playing? --- ANSWER:} 22. Qd4 $1 {
Centralizing the queen!} (22. Ne2 {, to bring the knight to d4, is also very
logical, although it then takes a little longer to introduce the white rook on
a1 into the game as the first rank is still blocked.}) 22... b6 23. Rh1 (23.
Re1 {is, of course, also possible, developing with tempo, but at the same time
allowing Black to relieve a bit of the pressure by exchanging the rooks with}
Re7 24. Rxe7 Qxe7 {.}) 23... a5 {EXERCISE: Now find a way to improve the
worst-placed white piece! --- ANSWER:} 24. Nd1 {The knight heads for a better
home on e3, from where it pressures the isolated f5-pawn.} Qf8 25. Ne3 {
QUESTION: Black's position looks very passive. In order to reduce the pressure
which set of pieces would he like to exchange? --- ANSWER:} Rf7 $1 {It seems
to me the best white piece is the queen and so Black challenges it along the
long diagonal by vacating the g7-square.} 26. b3 Qg7 27. Qxg7+ Kxg7 28. a3 Rf8
{The situation is still difficult for Black, but at least he has taken the
queens off. --- EXERCISE: Identify White's worst piece here and find a way to
improve it. --- ANSWER:} 29. Be2 $1 {The white bishop is doing nothing so
heads to d3 to pressure the isolated pawn.} Ne7 30. Bd3 h6 31. Rh5 Be8 {
Setting a little trap.} 32. Rh2 $1 (32. Nxf5+ Nxf5 33. Rxf5 {temporarily
misplaces the rook. After} Rh8 $1 {the threat of ...Bg6 cannot be stopped.}) ({
Likewise} 32. Rxf5 {allows the same trick with} Rh8 $1 {.}) 32... Bd7 33. Rh1 {
True to his style, Petrosian continues to watch and wait. Former World
Champion Max Euwe described him as "a python waiting to strike". Here White
has all the time in the world as any queenside break by Black will weaken his
position.} Rh8 {QUESTION: Can White continue to improve his minor pieces? ---
ANSWER:} 34. Nc2 $1 {Yes! The d4-square is better for the knight than the
e3-square, as from there it gains access to the outpost square on e6.} Kf6 35.
Nd4 Kg7 36. Be2 {The computer also thinks that White is better here, but
cannot find a good way to improve it.} ({One of the problems is that} 36. b4
axb4 37. axb4 Ra8 $1 {gives Black counterplay down the a-file.}) 36... Ng8 $6 (
36... Ra8 {to keep control of the a-file is safer.}) 37. b4 $1 {The python
strikes!} Nf6 38. Bd3 axb4 {Now the play becomes sharper.} (38... Kg6 39. bxa5
bxa5 40. Rb1 {is unpleasant for Black.}) 39. axb4 Kg6 {QUESTION: How should
White continue here? --- ANSWER:} 40. Ra1 $1 {Of course! Petrosian grabs the
a-file and prepares an invasion along the seventh rank.} Ng4+ 41. Ke2 ({White
must tread carefully:} 41. Kf3 $2 Re8 {gives Black serious chances down the
e-file, with a fork on e3 already threatened.}) 41... Re8+ 42. Kd2 Nf6 ({Black
would dearly love to invade with} 42... Re3 {, but the poor placement of his
bishop causes him problems:} 43. Ra7 $1 Rxg3 44. Rxc7 Nf2 $1 45. Bc2 Ne4+ 46.
Bxe4 fxe4 47. Rxd7 Rd3+ 48. Ke2 Rxd4 49. Rxd6+ Kf5 50. c5 {should be winning
for White.}) 43. Ra6 (43. Ra7 Rc8 {would transpose to the game.}) 43... Rb8 44.
Ra7 Rc8 {EXERCISE: Black remains very tied down, with his knight being the
only piece he can sensibly move. Petrosian sees a chance to improve his
d4-knight at the cost of a pawn. Can you see how? --- ANSWER:} 45. c5 $6 bxc5 (
{Not} 45... Nxd5 $2 46. c6 {and the bishop can't move due to the check on f5.})
46. bxc5 dxc5 47. Nf3 {This was the point. The knight heads further into the
black camp.} Kf7 $1 {Dogged defence.} ({Instead} 47... Nxd5 $2 {loses a piece
to} 48. Ne5+ {.}) 48. Ne5+ Ke7 49. Nxd7 Nxd7 50. Bxf5 {White has transformed
his advantage, as he now has bishop against knight and the c-pawns are doubled.
However, the exchange of one pair of minor pieces has made the position easier
for Black to defend, which is why I gave 45 c5 a dubious symbol.} Rf8 $1 51. g4
({Trading down to a rook and pawn ending seems to be just a draw:} 51. Bxd7
Kxd7 52. Ke3 (52. Ra6 Rg8) 52... Kd6 53. Ra6+ Kxd5 54. Rxh6 Re8+ 55. Kf3 c4 {.}
) 51... Kd6 $2 (51... Nf6 $1 {was a cheeky defence:} 52. Be6 Nxd5 $1 53. Bxd5
Rxf4 {and Black should hold as he will win the g- pawn and at the very worst 
(if he loses all his pawns) get a theoretically drawn rook against bishop and
rook endgame.}) 52. Bxd7 $1 Kxd7 53. Ke3 Re8+ $1 {Black cuts off the king from
the passed c-pawn.} 54. Kf3 (54. Kd3 Rg8 {was the point, when the g4-pawn is
not defensible.}) 54... Kd6 55. Ra6+ Kxd5 56. Rxh6 c4 {Compared to the note to
the move 51, the white g-pawn is one square further forward. In his notes
Petrosian assessed this position as winning, but it is still highly
complicated.} 57. Rh1 $2 ({I won't show you all the analysis, but the key line
runs} 57. Rh7 $1 {. The rook belongs behind the passed pawns for the moment.
After} c6 58. Rd7+ Kc5 59. Rd1 c3 60. g5 Kc4 61. g6 c2 62. Rc1 Kc3 63. f5 Rg8
64. Kf4 Kd2 65. Rxc2+ Kxc2 66. Kg5 c5 67. f6 c4 68. f7 Rxg6+ 69. Kxg6 c3 70.
f8=Q {White wins!}) 57... c3 58. g5 c5 59. Rd1+ (59. g6 Rg8 60. f5 Ke5 $1 61.
Kg4 Kf6 62. Rc1 c4 63. Rxc3 Rc8 {is also holding.}) 59... Kc4 60. g6 c2 61. Rc1
Kd3 62. f5 {EXERCISE: One last test, which is not relevant to this chapter,
but good for you anyway! Find the drawing move here! --- ANSWER:} Rg8 $1 {
Halting the pawns in their tracks is crucial.} (62... Kd2 $2 {should lose to}
63. Rxc2+ Kxc2 64. g7 c4 65. f6 Rg8 66. f7 Rxg7 67. f8=Q {as the black king
and rook are too far away from each other.}) 63. Kf4 Kd2 64. Rxc2+ Kxc2 65. Kg5
c4 66. f6 c3 67. f7 ({Here this epic battle was agreed drawn as after} 67. f7
Rxg6+ 68. Kxg6 Kb1 69. f8=Q c2 {there is nothing more to play for, so long as
you remember the trick} 70. Qb4+ Ka1 71. Qc3+ Kb1 72. Qb3+ Ka1 $1 {.}) (67. --
{Summary: Petrosian probed and prodded Fischer's position for some time, not
rushing but instead 'massaging' his slight advantage by using the worst piece
strategy. Against a weaker player this probably would have resulted in Black
losing patience and committing hara-kiri, but here Black stayed patient. In
the end an interesting rook and pawn endgame was reached and with dogged
defence Fischer managed to draw.}) 1/2-1/2

