{You must be so careful about the placement of your trickiest pieces.
Tseshkovsky demonstrated a model example of how to handle the knight in the
first game of the chapter, whilst Kurnosov under time pressure allowed his
knight to be trapped. I will now show another example of how not to handle the
knight.} 31. b4 {Up to this point the game has been quite balanced, but here I
made a pretty dumb move. --- EXERCISE: There are four squares for the knight
that don't lose material. Which are the best and worst?} Nb7 $2 {ANSWER: It
definitely isn't this one! The principle of centralization is a powerful one
and I momentarily forgot about it. Watch what happens to this poor beast.} (
31... Ne6 $1) ({and} 31... Ne4 {are about tied for top spot. Both offer Black
a small advantage I think}) ({but} 31... Nd7 $6 {is quite ugly as the knight
again doesn't have a route out.}) 32. Rh7 $1 Kf7 ({Or} 32... Rg8 33. Bb3 Kd6
34. a5 {and again the knight is completely miserable.}) 33. Bb3 {Suddenly
Black is on the back foot, having to parry White's threats.} Rd8 34. Rh1 {
EXERCISE: With one piece (out of four) out of play Black must tread very
carefully. Can you see a way of getting the knight back into the game?} (34. f5
Kg8 35. Rh3 {followed by a queenside pawn push is also good.}) 34... e4 $2 ({
ANSWER:} 34... Nd6 $1 {is a surprising pawn sacrifice, but it brings the
knight back to life:} 35. Bxd5+ Ke7 {(threatening ...Nxb5)} 36. Bc6 exf4 37.
Bxf4 Bc3 {keeps Black very much in the game.}) 35. Rd1 Ke6 36. Be1 Be3 37. Bg3
$6 (37. Bxd5+ $1 {would have been a nice shot to finish things off:} Rxd5 38.
f5+ Rxf5 39. gxf5+ Kxf5 40. Rd7 {and the black knight is trapped.}) 37... f5
38. gxf5+ (38. Bh4 {would have been even better.}) 38... Kxf5 39. Bh4 Rd7 (
39... Ra8 {would have been more stubborn, but after} 40. Rxd5+ Kg4 41. Bg5 Bxf4
42. Bxf4 Kxf4 43. Rd7 Nd8 44. Rxg7 Ke3 45. Kb2 {the white pieces still
dominate the board.}) 40. Bxd5 Kxf4 (40... Rc7 41. Re1 Kxf4 42. Bg3+ {is
annoying.}) 41. Rf1+ Ke5 42. Bc6 {The knight on b7 has not moved since move 31.
It is now lost by force and so is the game.} Rd4 ({If} 42... Rc7 43. Bg3+ {.})
43. Bg3+ Ke6 44. Bxb7 {and White won in 57 moves.} (44. -- {Summary: I hope
these last two examples have highlighted how important it is to keep your
pieces happy, especially your knights as they are more easily trapped and
immobilized than your other forces. Here I forgot about my knight temporarily
and paid a heavy price.}) 1-0

