Rf3 Qh5 21. Bxc5+ Ke8 {EXERCISE: Now the king is stuck in the centre for good,
White can rest a little more easily. Can you find a way to open up more lines
to the king? --- ANSWER:} 22. c3 $1 Rb7 23. Qa4+ Rd7 (23... Nd7 24. Rxe6+ fxe6
25. Rf8# {was a pretty mate I was hoping for.}) 24. Qc6 Rad8 $2 (24... Rb8 {
keeps the game going, though after} 25. Bxa7 Rbd8 26. Bc5 Rb8 27. Bd6 Rbd8 28.
Bb4 $1 Rb8 29. Qc5 {White wins due to the weak dark squares.}) 25. Rxe6+ {.
Summary: Similarly to Kupreichik's game, using a series of threatening moves
White managed to prevent Black from getting his king to safety and organizing
his defences. Gradually his advantage built as his pieces became more and more
active. Most certainly the initiative and attack outweighed the tripled
isolated pawns White gave himself.} 1-0

