1. Nf3 Nf6 2. d4 e6 3. c4 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 O-O 6. e3 {The game starts
quietly enough.} h6 7. Bh4 b6 8. Qb3 Bb7 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Rd1 {
A prophylactic move, White reinforces his strong point on d4, whilst if the
only black pawn break (...c7-c5) occurs, then he will also have pressure down
the d-file. Having said this, the move played doesn't get White any nearer to
castling and Kasparov is quick to try and use this. --- EXERCISE: Can you see
how? --- ANSWER:} c5 $5 {Anyway! Black tries to open up the game for his
bishop-pair.} 12. dxc5 ({White, of course, doesn't have to accept this pawn,
but otherwise Black will get some queenside space advantage after} 12. Be2 c4
13. Qc2 Nc6 {which would defeat the purpose of the queen sortie to b3 on move
8.}) 12... Nd7 $1 {The knight heads for c5, forcing the queen to retreat.} 13.
c6 $5 {An interesting moment. Magerramov, who himself was a very strong player,
decides to try and limit the activity of the black pieces.} (13. cxb6 Nc5 $1
14. Qc2 axb6 15. Be2 {would have been another way for White to play, though
after something like} Bxc3+ 16. bxc3 Qe7 17. O-O Rfc8 {Black would have had
good pressure against the white queenside pawns.}) 13... Bxc6 14. Nd4 $6 {Very
natural, but almost certainly a mistake. --- EXERCISE: If Black plays quietly
here, with something like 14...Bb7 then White will simply play 15 Be2 followed
by 0-0. Can you see a way to force the issue instead?} (14. Nxd5 Nc5 15. Nxf6+
Qxf6 16. Qc3 $1 Qxc3+ 17. bxc3 {would have been safer.}) 14... Bxd4 $1 {ANSWER:
A difficult move to play! Black gives up his uncontested dark-squared bishop,
but in doing so creates concrete threats.} 15. Rxd4 (15. exd4 Qg5 $1 {makes it
difficult to develop the f1-bishop, whilst also threatening ...Re8+.}) 15...
Nc5 16. Qd1 {If only the piece on d4 was a knight, White would be laughing. As
it is the rook will be forced back.} Ne6 17. Rd2 {QUESTION: But now what? ---
ANSWER:} d4 $1 {Opening the diagonal for his bishop and the e-file for his
rook at the cost of a pawn. This was the idea Kasparov had in mind when he
played his 14th move.} 18. exd4 (18. Ne2 {was probably better, though Black
could keep the pressure up with} Qe7 19. Nxd4 Nxd4 20. Rxd4 Rad8 $1 {.}) 18...
Re8 {The black pieces have sprung to life.} 19. f3 {Trying desperately to get
the bishop to e2.} ({Alternatively: It is not possible to block the e-file
with the bishop as} 19. Be2 Bxg2 20. Rg1 Nf4 {is too strong.}) (19. d5 $1 {
trying to counterattack was probably the best practical try, though I suspect
Kasparov would have found} Nf4+ 20. Be2 Nxg2+ 21. Kf1 Bd7 $1 22. Rg1 (22. Kxg2
Qg5+ 23. Kf1 Bh3+ 24. Ke1 Qg2 {is very painful}) 22... Nh4 {with an ongoing
initiative.}) 19... Bxf3 {Smash! This opens the short h4-e1 diagonal for the
queen.} 20. gxf3 (20. Qxf3 {would lose the queen for two pieces to} Ng5+ 21.
Qe2 Rxe2+ {.}) 20... Qh4+ 21. Rf2 Nxd4+ (21... Nf4+ $1 {seems to be even
better, as after} 22. Be2 Ng2+ 23. Kd2 Qxd4+ 24. Kc1 Qxf2 {White is doomed.})
22. Be2 Nxf3+ 23. Kf1 Qh3+ 24. Rg2 Nh4 ({I also quite like} 24... Rad8 {,
bringing the final piece into the attack.}) 25. Rhg1 Rad8 26. Qe1 {EXERCISE:
White plans 27 Qg3, trying to exchange the queens whilst threatening mate on
g7. Can you stop this plan whilst creating a threat of your own? --- ANSWER:}
Rd3 $1 {A great move. The idea is to play ...Rf3+.} 27. Qf2 Nf3 28. Rh1 Rde3
29. Rhg1 {White has given up.} (29. Qg3 {would have been better, but Kasparov
would still have been winning easily.}) 29... Kh8 {Despite the mass of
defensive pieces around the white king, Magerramov is completely tied up.} ({
However,} 29... Rxc3 $1 {would have been the most powerful finish. Perhaps
Kasparov started to relax as it was just a training game? It's all over after}
30. bxc3 Nxh2+ 31. Ke1 Qxc3+ 32. Kd1 Rd8+ {.}) 30. Rh1 b5 {. White had
understandably had enough.} 0-1

