13. Bd3 {QUESTION: How to seize the initiative here as Black? --- ANSWER:} f5
$1 {Vassily Ivanchuk is superb at spotting such chances. Black looks to open
the centre with the white king still residing there.} 14. f3 $2 {EXERCISE:
White's last move loosened the dark squares too much, a theme we will revisit
later in the chapter. What should Black do here?} (14. Qxg6 Nxg6 15. O-O-O {
was safer, although Black's position would have been very comfortable after}
Nf4 16. Bc4+ Be6 17. Bxe6+ Nxe6 {.}) 14... Qh6 $1 {ANSWER: Very logical. With
no obvious escape for the white king, Black chooses to keep the queens on. He
also threatens the nasty ...f5-f4, trapping the queen.} 15. Nd4 f4 16. Qf2 c5
17. Bc4+ (17. Ne2 c4 $1 18. Bxc4+ d5 {would win a piece.}) 17... d5 $1 {Not
giving White the chance to reorganize her pieces. Ivanchuk's energy over the
next few moves is tireless.} 18. exd5 cxd4 19. d6+ Be6 20. dxe7 {QUESTION: But
what now? --- ANSWER:} Bxc4 $1 (20... Rfe8 21. Qe2 $1 {defends for the moment.}
) 21. exf8=Q+ Rxf8 {Now that the smoke has cleared White is an exchange up,
but her king is still stuck hopelessly in the centre.} 22. Bxd4 {EXERCISE: Can
you find a simple way to finish the game? --- ANSWER:} Re8+ 23. Kd2 Rd8 $1 {
The pin decides things.} 24. c3 c5 {. Not only will Black get two fantastic
bishops for the rook, but the white king cannot hope to survive in the centre,
so Muzychuk resigned.} 0-1

