{It would be criminal of me not to demonstrate at least one game played by
Mikhail Tal, arguably the greatest attacking chess player of all time. In the
next game the space advantage White achieves is the precursor to his seizing
the initiative.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f4 Qb6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. Be2 Nbd7
{EXERCISE: Can you find the way to seize the initiative already? --- ANSWER:}
7. e5 $1 {White grabs space whilst threatening the knight.} Nd5 8. O-O {An
interesting decision. Tal lets Black double his c-pawns in order to gain
activity for his rook along the b-file.} Nxc3 ({It is already not so easy to
suggest a good way of developing for Black, as} 8... e6 {would be well met by}
9. Ne4 $1 {, taking advantage of the weak d6-square and preparing the advance
of the c-pawn.}) 9. bxc3 e6 ({Here Black could have won a pawn with} 9... Bxf3
10. Bxf3 dxe5 (10... d5 11. e6 $1 {would have been a typical blow to disrupt
the Black development - see Chapter Three for more on this}) 11. fxe5 Nxe5 {,
but after something like} 12. Be4 Nd7 13. Bf4 {White has a big lead in
development and the bishop-pair as compensation.}) 10. Ng5 Bxe2 11. Qxe2 {The
knight on g5, combined with the queen on e2, means that Black is in quite a
tough spot already.} h6 {EXERCISE: What did White play here? See how far you
can calculate down the forcing line that arises.} (11... Be7 12. exd6 Bxd6 13.
Nxe6 $1 fxe6 14. Qxe6+ Be7 15. Re1 {would win a couple of pawns, as} Qd8 {,
can be met by} ({and} 15... O-O-O 16. Qxe7 Rde8 17. Qxe8+ Rxe8 18. Rxe8+) 16.
Ba3 {.}) 12. Nxf7 $1 {(ANSWER)} ({Of course, the knight is not going to go
back:} 12. Ne4 d5 13. Nd6+ Bxd6 14. exd6 {would give Black time to castle.}) (
12. Qh5 g6 13. Qh3 {would, though, be another way to maintain the initiative,
as then the e6-pawn comes under attack.}) 12... Kxf7 13. f5 $1 {Black cannot
be allowed to play ...g7-g6, securing control of the important f5-square.} dxe5
14. fxe6+ ({It seems that} 14. Qh5+ Ke7 15. fxe6 Kxe6 {is even stronger for
White, as the queen is better placed.}) 14... Kxe6 {QUESTION: Can White stop
Black running his king over to c7? --- ANSWER: Yes!} 15. Rb1 $1 {Cheeky. Tal
uses the open file to maximum effect, as he can force the black king to a dark
square so that his discovered check works.} Qxb1 {Simagin decided to return
some material. Unfortunately for him, though, Tal's initiative persists.} (
15... Qa6 16. Qg4+ Kd6 17. dxe5+ Kc7 18. Bf4 {is very bad for Black.}) 16. Qc4+
Kd6 17. Ba3+ Kc7 18. Rxb1 Bxa3 {EXERCISE: White must keep up the initiative!
Material-wise Black is ahead still, so he cannot be allowed to reorganize. Can
you find a way? --- ANSWER:} 19. Qb3 {Thanks to this move, which hits the
weaknesses on a3 and b7, White can keep the attack going despite his lack of
pieces.} Be7 20. Qxb7+ Kd6 21. dxe5+ Nxe5 {And still there should be no let up.
Tal pushes the king even further into the open and the king-hunt begins.} 22.
Rd1+ Ke6 23. Qb3+ Kf5 24. Rf1+ Ke4 ({Forced, as} 24... Kg6 25. Qe6+ Bf6 26.
Qf5+ Kf7 27. Qxe5 $1 {wins the knight.}) 25. Re1+ Kf5 {Now that queen and rook
cannot give any more checks the reserves arrive!} 26. g4+ $1 Kf6 27. Rf1+ Kg6
28. Qe6+ Kh7 29. Qxe5 {White is winning and the rest is should be a matter of
technique. Tal complicates the issue a little bit though.} Rhe8 30. Rf7 Bf8 31.
Qf5+ Kg8 32. Kf2 $6 {A little bit risky. Black gets a couple of dangerous
checks in now.} (32. Kf1 {would have been safer.}) 32... Bc5+ 33. Kg3 Re3+ 34.
Kh4 Rae8 {EXERCISE: Can you find a way to minimize the danger to your king
here?} (34... Be7+ 35. g5 $1 {forced,} ({as} 35. Kh5 Rd8 $1 {threatens to win
the queen with ...Rd5}) 35... Bxg5+ 36. Kh5 {seems to still be enough for
White.}) 35. Rxg7+ $1 {ANSWER: Tal removes the dangerous g-pawn.} ({Instead} 
35. Qg6 Be7+ 36. g5 {allows} Bf6 $3 {which is a great computer-generated
defence, blocking the rook's path back and preparing some deadly checks for
Black: for instance,} 37. Rxf6 R8e4+ 38. Kh5 Rh3# {.}) 35... Kxg7 36. Qxc5 {
Now the white king is secure and the queen has enough pawns to help her win
the ending.} R8e6 37. Qxa7+ Kg6 38. Qa8 Kf6 39. a4 Ke5 40. a5 Kd5 41. Qd8+ Ke4
42. a6 Kf3 43. a7 Re2 44. Qd3+ R2e3 45. Qxe3+ {. Summary: This game concludes
our examination of how to use the initiative to start a direct attack on the
king. Remember that it is the ability to make threats of your own, rather than
defending against them, that gives you the initiative. A lead in development,
a space advantage or a target for attack for your pieces (such as an uncastled
king) are all good indicators that a dangerous initiative might be there. If
blunders are not made in a game of chess, then the only way to win is by
attacking and only the side with the initiative can attack! Thus I would
recommend trying to seize the initiative at the earliest stage possible.} 1-0

