13. Rd1 {EXERCISE: Having wasted a little time earlier in the game (with ...c6
followed by ...c5 in the opening), Black finds himself under a little bit of
pressure. What would you do here? --- ANSWER:} Qe7 $1 {A good move, removing
the queen from the d-file and defending the bishop. Having loose pieces is a
great way to lose quickly in the opening!} 14. Bf3 {Gelfand logically puts
some more pressure on the Isolani. --- QUESTION: What should Black do about
it? --- ANSWER:} O-O $1 (14... Rd8 {would have been the choice of a lot of
people I'm sure, but Anand favours activity over the pawn.}) 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16.
Bxd5 Nxd5 17. Rxd5 Rac8 {By giving up the pawn Black has taken a slight lead
in development.} 18. Bd2 {Interestingly Gelfand gives it back to secure full
development and retain a very small edge. Being the World Championship it is
very likely that this position was heavily analysed before the start of the
match!} (18. Qe2 Qe4 $1 19. Qd3 Qxd3 20. Rxd3 Rfd8 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 {keeps the
initiative for Black into the ending, which should be enough for a draw after
something like} 22. Kf1 Rd1+ 23. Ke2 Rh1 {.}) 18... Bxe3 19. Bc3 Bb6 20. Qf5 {
Preparing Rd7.} Qe6 21. Qf3 (21. Qxe6 fxe6 22. Rd2 Rfd8 {is nothing for White.}
) 21... f6 22. h4 Qc6 23. h5 {EXERCISE: Gelfand looks to probe on the kingside,
trying to fix the kingside pawns on dark squares. What should Vishy do about
this? --- ANSWER:} Rfd8 {Offering the gradual exchange of more pieces.} (23...
h6 {was also possible and even Kasparov and Svidler, who were commentating at
the time, didn't think this was a very serious problem for Black as the weak
pawns are on one side of the board only.}) 24. Rxd8+ (24. Rad1 Rxd5 25. Rxd5
Rd8 26. Rxd8+ Bxd8 27. Qxc6 bxc6 {should also be equal.}) 24... Rxd8 25. Qxc6
bxc6 26. Re1 {EXERCISE: The last point when you need to be precise. Find
Anand's next move. --- ANSWER:} Kf7 $1 {This secures the draw, as the entry
squares on e6 and e7 are covered.} ({Trying to enter a rook ending immediately
with} 26... Bd4 27. Bxd4 Rxd4 28. Rc1 {would be a touch better for White.}) 27.
g4 Bd4 28. Rc1 Bxc3 29. Rxc3 Rd4 {. Summary: Anatoly Karpov once said: "It is
dangerous to maintain equality at the cost of placing the pieces passively."
Always try to have in the back of your mind the idea that active play (in this
case giving up the weak d-pawn) is nearly always better than passive play.
Anand did a good job of neutralizing any white advantage in this game by using
this idea, whilst Gelfand also favoured active play and completing development
on move 18.} 1/2-1/2

