{Prophylactic Thinking in the Opening: There are many examples of prophylaxis
in the opening. It is a particularly important idea to remember for the side
that possesses the centre. Prophylactic thinking can often be applied to
prevent it coming under attack. Witness the following passage of play from the
main line of the Grünfeld Defence.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5
5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 {Black has conceded the centre, but plans to attack the
white central pawns as fast as he can.} 7. Bc4 c5 8. Be3 O-O {QUESTION: What
is the best move for White here: 9 Ne2 or 9 Nf3? ANSWER:} 9. Ne2 $1 ({
White 'foresees' that his d4-pawn will come under rapid attack after} 9. Nf3
Nc6 10. O-O Bg4 {.}) {Now after} 9... Nc6 10. O-O Bg4 {White has} 11. f3 {and
the centre is secure, at least for the moment.} *

