{Anatoly Karpov is seen as one of the truly great modern prophylactic players.
Here he squeezes the life out of one his biggest rivals of the 80's and 90's,
Artur Yusupov.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 {The Open
Variation of the Ruy Lopez.} 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6 9. c3 Bc5 10. Nbd2
O-O 11. Bc2 Bf5 (11... Nxf2 12. Rxf2 f6) ({and} 11... f5 12. Nb3 Bb6 13. Nfd4 {
are the main alternatives.}) 12. Nb3 Bg6 13. Nfd4 Bxd4 (13... Nxe5 $4 14. Bxe4
Bxd4 ({if} 14... Bxe4 15. Nxc5) 15. Qxd4 {just wins a piece.}) 14. cxd4 a5 15.
Be3 a4 16. Nd2 a3 17. Nxe4 axb2 18. Rb1 Bxe4 19. Rxb2 Qd7 20. Bd3 Bxd3 21. Qxd3
Rfb8 {EXERCISE: What is the best way to restrict the queenside plan of ...Na5-c4? --- ANSWER:} 22. Rfb1 $1 {For the moment Black is forced to deal with
the threat to his b5-pawn.} ({White could have immediately started kingside
operations with} 22. f4 {, but after} Na5 23. f5 Nc4 {Black would get serious
queenside counterplay.}) ({Likewise,} 22. Rxb5 Rxb5 23. Qxb5 Nxe5 $1 {offers
White no advantage.}) 22... b4 23. h3 {Well, Yusupov wasn't threatening
back-rank mate, but in some positions if the a- and b-pawns get exchanged then
he might be. The move is also quite handy in that it stops the black queen
coming to its most active square on g4.} h6 {Black responds in turn.} (23...
Ra3 $4 24. Qxa3 bxa3 25. Rxb8+ Nd8 26. Bg5 {is an example of the back-rank
issues that Yusupov was faced with.}) 24. Rc1 {QUESTION: How does this prevent
...Na5?} Rb6 ({ANSWER:} 24... Na5 25. Qb1 $1 Nc4 $2 26. Rxb4 Rxb4 27. Qxb4 Rxa2
$4 28. Qb8+ Kh7 29. Qb1+ {is the deep tactical point, forking king and rook.})
25. Qb1 {Pressuring the b4-pawn again.} (25. Rc5 $1 Na5 26. Qb1 {is also good
enough.}) 25... Rab8 26. Rc5 $1 Nd8 27. Rcc2 Nc6 28. Qc1 $1 {From a
psychological point of view this prophylactic strategy is very frustrating for
the opponent. Without an active plan Yusupov is forced to simply defend his
weaknesses and wait.} R8b7 {EXERCISE: What was the idea behind Black's last
move and how do we prevent his plan? --- ANSWER:} 29. Rc5 $1 {With ...Rb8-b7
Black defended the c7-pawn. This means that his knight can move. As we know it
would like to be on c4, where it is on an outpost square and hitting the rook.
In fact if it gets there Black is doing well. Therefore Karpov's move is very
strong and very logical. Not only does the rook prevent ...Na5-c4, it also
targets the d5-pawn.} Ne7 (29... Nd8 {, trying to re-route the knight, would I
suspect have been met by} 30. Ra5 Ne6 31. f4 $1 {.}) 30. Kh2 {QUESTION: What
is the idea behind Karpov's last move? --- ANSWER: He wants to play Rb2-c2,
without allowing the ...b4-b3 pawn break which will give Black activity based
on the potential pin from queen to king along the first rank.} Nf5 $2 {Getting
frustrated, Black loses the c7-pawn.} 31. Rbc2 Rg6 (31... Nxe3 32. fxe3 b3 33.
axb3 Rxb3 34. Rxc7 Rxc7 35. Rxc7 Qf5 {would have given Black some activity and
perhaps better chances of survival.}) 32. Rxc7 Rxc7 33. Rxc7 Qb5 34. g4 Nh4 35.
Rc8+ Kh7 {EXERCISE: How do you prevent any penetration here? --- ANSWER:} 36.
Qd1 $1 {This covers the weak light squares on d3, e2 and f3.} Qa6 37. Rc2 f5
38. Kg3 $1 {Now the black knight is trapped.} fxg4 39. Kxh4 gxh3 40. f4 Qe6 {
EXERCISE: One last throw of the dice by Yusupov. The white king looks
vulnerable, but can you see a good way that we can cover him? --- ANSWER:} 41.
Qh5 {Defending the f5- and g4-squares.} Qe7+ (41... Qa6 {, trying to get in
around the back, is met by} 42. Re2 {.}) 42. Kxh3 Qf7 43. Rh2 Qd7+ 44. f5 {.
Summary: The main prophylactic moments of the game came on moves 21-28, when
White frustrated Black's attempted queenside counterplay. Always be thinking
about your opponent's plans just as much as your own!} 1-0

