d6-pawn and increases his control over the c5-square. --- QUESTION: Is there a
way to generate some counterplay as Black and how seriously should we take the
b3-b4 break? --- ANSWER:} Rb8 $1 {An exclamation mark? Well, Tibor Karolyi in
his book Endgame Virtuoso gave it two! The idea is to prepare the ...b7-b5
pawn break after the bishop moves.} 35. Rc4 ({The answer to the second part of
the question was that} 35. b4 $6 {is not good as White gives himself a
weakness on a4:} axb4 36. Bxb4 Ra8 $1 37. Ra2 Bd4 {and Black stands well.})
35... Bd4 36. f4 {EXERCISE: Spassky tries to become active on the kingside.
How should Black react? --- ANSWER:} g6 $1 {Preventing the pawn advance.} ({
After} 36... b5 37. axb5 Rxb5 38. f5+ Kd5 39. Nc3+ Bxc3 40. Rxc3 {a draw would
be the most likely outcome.}) 37. Ng3 {Again preparing the f4-f5 advance.} exf4
38. Rxd4 fxg3 39. Kxg3 Rc8 {. Black is now better. He has the more active king,
the open c-file and a superb square for his knight on e5. Karpov went on to
win after 55 moves.} 0-1

