1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {Overprotection of pawn chains (such as the d4-e5
chain here) in closed positions can be particularly important, as the
opponent's pawn breaks against such chains will be easier to manage.} Bf5 4.
Bd3 {White chooses a quiet line.} (4. Nf3) (4. h4) ({and} 4. Nd2 {are more
popular nowadays.}) 4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 e6 {EXERCISE: Let us take a moment to
think about how best to develop our minor pieces. If we go with the idea that
our centre is going to come under attack at a later stage with the typical
breaks ...c6-c5 and/or ...f7-f6, what is the best way to continue? --- ANSWER:}
6. Ne2 {White doesn't commit his f-pawn yet and remains flexible. I like this
move as any premature ...f7-f6 break will now leave e6 to be attacked by the
white knight (via f4).} ({Instead} 6. Nf3 {leaves the knight on b1 without a
purpose:} c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. a3 c4 9. Qc2 Nge7 {left Black with a good position
in De Gremont-A.Karpov, San Giorgio (simul) 1995.}) 6... Qb6 7. O-O Qa6 8. Qd1
{White, of course, doesn't wish to exchange queens at such an early stage.
With a solid pawn structure and no weaknesses Black would be fairly
comfortable in the endgame.} Nd7 {EXERCISE: Back to the concept of
overprotection. Where does the knight on b1 now belong? --- ANSWER:} 9. Nd2 $1
{The knight heads for f3. This set-up of white knights is also seen in the
French Tarrasch, another opening which can lead to a closed centre.} Ne7 10.
Nf3 Ng6 $6 {Perhaps a small inaccuracy.} ({I think the optimal square for this
knight is c6, so would have been more inclined to play something like} 10... c5
11. c3 Nc6 {with a solid position for Black.}) 11. Re1 {Nimzowitsch remains
true to his prophylactic style, discouraging ...f7-f6 even further.} ({However,
a case could have been made here for the typical attacking move} 11. h4 $5 c5 (
11... h5 {simply gives White a beautiful square on g5 for one of his minor
pieces}) 12. h5 Ne7 13. c3 {and White can claim a small advantage due to his
extra space.}) 11... Bb4 12. c3 Ba5 $6 {The bishop would be much better
employed on e7, discouraging the advance of the h-pawn and covering the
important g5-square. --- EXERCISE: Let's keep trying to think like
Nimzowitsch! Can you find another move to increase the defence of the centre?}
({Therefore} 12... Be7 $1 {should have been preferred.}) 13. Bf4 {(ANSWER) I
don't think this move is strictly necessary, but it is interesting to see how
these white pieces come alive later in the game.} ({Again, I think that} 13. h4
$1 {is the most testing, but that wouldn't be thinking like Nimzowitsch!})
13... O-O (13... Nxf4 $2 {would be a positional mistake, as then the white
knight comes to life via f4:} 14. Nxf4 O-O 15. Nh5 {leaves the black kingside
uncomfortable.}) 14. Bg3 {Removing the sensitive bishop from any possible
exchange.} Bc7 {Here we can see that White's plan of removing the possibility
of the ...f6 pawn break (and also in this case for the moment ...c6-c5) has
stifled Black's counterplay. --- QUESTION: How would you proceed in this
middlegame? --- ANSWER:} 15. Ng5 {The conditions are met for a kingside attack
- the pawn on e5 cramps the black position. The attack, however, must be built
up slowly.} Rfe8 (15... c5 {should have been played, seeking to pressurize the
white centre a bit.}) 16. Nf4 {Seeking to exchange off a defender of the black
kingside.} Nh8 $6 {I don't like this - Black is playing too passively.} (16...
Nxf4 17. Bxf4 h6 18. Nh3 c5 {still leaves Giese in reasonable shape.}) 17. Qg4
Nf8 {EXERCISE: Over the last few moves White has steadily improved his
position. What should he play now?} 18. Re3 {Without any direct black
counterplay Nimzowitsch seeks to gather more attacking forces on the kingside.}
({ANSWER:} 18. Nh5 $1 {should probably have been preferred. The knight targets
both the g7-pawn and the f6-square. For example,} Nhg6 19. Qf3 Re7 20. Nf6+ $3
{is a brilliant sacrifice which highlights how useful that e5-pawn is! After}
Kh8 (20... gxf6 21. exf6 Rd7 22. Qh5 {followed by Qh6-g7 is devastating}) 21.
h4 $1 h6 22. Nh3 {White has a very dangerous attack with h4-h5 coming: for
instance,} gxf6 23. exf6 Rd7 24. Bxc7 Rxc7 25. h5 {.}) 18... b6 $2 {Again
Black just doesn't respond quickly enough and sense the danger in time.} (18...
h6 {would be better, removing this dangerous knight:} 19. Nf3 Nhg6 {with only
a slight edge to White.}) 19. Nh5 Nhg6 20. Rf3 Re7 21. Nf6+ $1 {Finally the
enemy is engaged and note the use of the overprotected e5-pawn.} Kh8 {EXERCISE:
Finish Black off! Nimzowitsch couldn't find the win here, but can you?} (21...
gxf6 22. exf6 Rd7 23. Bxc7 Rxc7 24. Qh3 {is curtains. The g7-square is too
weak.}) 22. Qh5 $2 ({ANSWER:} 22. Nfxh7 $1 {is completely crushing:} Nxh7 23.
Nxf7+ Rxf7 24. Rxf7 {and Black will lose material or perhaps get mated if the
h-pawn arrives on h5!}) 22... h6 {Suddenly the game is back in the balance and
White has to win it all over again. I will give the remaining moves without
comment for you to play over. Suffice to say that had Nimzowitsch found the
win he would have proclaimed his triumphant overprotection strategy. Instead
we will have to do it for him!} 23. Kh1 Bd8 24. b4 Qe2 25. Rg1 a5 26. Ng4 Kg8
27. Nxf7 Qd2 28. Nxd8 Rxd8 29. bxa5 bxa5 30. Bh4 Nxh4 31. Qxh4 Ng6 32. Qh5 Kh7
33. a4 Rb8 34. h3 Rb3 35. Rg3 Nf4 36. Qxh6+ $1 {A stylish finish!} gxh6 37.
Nf6+ Kh8 38. Rg8# {. Summary: Overprotection is an advanced form of
prophylaxis and is usually applied to central squares. It is useful in denying
the opponent any tactical opportunities and, as we saw in this game,
overprotection of e5 led to a powerful kingside attack for White.} 1-0

