{There is a simpler way!: Fortunately for us there is a much easier way of
calculating the material balance and that is by cancelling the equivalent
pieces of our army and our opponent's. Let us take a completely random
position that has popped into my head to see what I mean.} 1. -- {Remember
that at this stage it is not important to do anything else other than
calculate the material balance. So the cancellation method is to compare the
equivalent pieces in the two positions. In this case it is as follows:} (1. --
{1) Both sides have a king, so no difference there (always the case).}) (1. --
{2) Both sides have a queen: we can cancel those out.}) (1. -- {3) Both sides
have two rooks: we can cancel them.}) (1. -- {4) White has two knights, Black
has two knights, so we can cancel them.}) (1. -- {5) Black has an extra bishop:
three points to him.}) (1. -- {6) White has eight pawns, Black has six: two
points to White.}) (1. -- {Conclusion: Black has a lead in simple terms of
material of one point. In more advanced terminology we would say a piece for
two pawns, as stronger players tend to stick to the points system only very
loosely. The relative activity of the pieces affects their worth.}) *

