{Witness the following fascinating game, full of imbalances aplenty} 1. e4 c5
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9.
Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c3 Bg5 12. Nc2 O-O 13. Be2 {EXERCISE: By evaluating
the relative merits of the minor pieces here try to come up with a good
strategy for Black. --- ANSWER:} Ne7 $1 {Very sensibly Black seeks to try and
undermine the superior white knight on d5. One of Black's main advantages in
this position is the bishop-pair, so he tries to maintain that advantage by
using his knight for the exchange.} 14. Ncb4 {White of course is in no mood to
'repair' the hole on d5 by capturing back with his pawn or queen.} a5 15. Nxe7+
Qxe7 16. Nd5 Qb7 17. Qd3 {The white queen eyes up the b5-pawn.} b4 18. cxb4 (
18. c4 {would appear to make sense, keeping an iron grip on the d5-square, but
there are no real targets in the black position:} Be6 19. Rd1 a4 20. O-O Ra5 $1
{is a typical Sicilian motif and would be a creative way of trying to fix a
pawn at d5. Black is better here as his bishop exerts more influence over the
game than its counterpart by controlling the c1-square. With all the heavy
pieces on the board Black has every chance of converting his advantage.}) 18...
axb4 19. Qg3 h6 20. O-O {QUESTION: What should Black's strategy be here? ---
ANSWER:} Kh8 {To undermine the d5-knight. In order to do that Black must play
for ...f7-f5, so he sensibly moves his king off the weak a2-g8 diagonal.} ({
The premature} 20... f5 {allows White into the black camp after} 21. h4 $1 Bd8
22. Qg6 {with unpleasant pressure.}) 21. Qb3 {Hitting the weak pawn on b4.} Rb8
({The immediate} 21... f5 {is also quite possible:} 22. exf5 Bxf5 23. Nxb4 Be4
24. f3 Bh7 {gives Black good compensation for the sacrificed pawn due to his
central pawn mass and White's weak dark squares.}) 22. Rad1 f5 {The pawn break
finally arrives.} 23. Bf3 Qa7 {Removing the queen from the long diagonal.} 24.
Nxb4 $6 (24. exf5 Bxf5 25. Nxb4 {was safer, but the dynamism of the black
position would still be evident after} e4 26. Be2 e3 $1 27. f3 Qb6 {, with a
real thorn in the side on e3.}) 24... fxe4 25. Bxe4 Bg4 $1 {The bishops'
collective power is evident.} 26. a3 {White is forced to sacrifice the
exchange,} ({as} 26. Rxd6 Qc5 {forks the rook and knight.}) (26. Rb1 Qc5 27. a3
Be2 {also collects the exchange due to the weakness on f2.}) 26... Bxd1 27.
Qxd1 {QUESTION: How should Black defend the d6-pawn? --- ANSWER:} Rbc8 $1 {He
shouldn't! Hopefully by now we are thinking first and foremost about active,
aggressive moves. Tying down a piece to defence of the backward pawn makes
little sense.} 28. g3 (28. Qxd6 Qxf2+ 29. Rxf2 Rc1+ 30. Rf1 Rcxf1# {is the
tactical justification.}) 28... Rc1 29. Qe2 Rxf1+ {there was a tactical shot
here that black must have rejected. What was it?} (29... Rxf2 $5 30. Qxf2 Be3 {
looks very tempting, but after} 31. Kg2 Bxf2 32. Rxc1 {White has very good
control of the light squares and it is the black king that must be a little
careful.}) 30. Kxf1 Qd4 (30... Be3 {again looks good and to be honest I'm not
so sure why Shirov didn't go for this - it seems to force a weakening of the
dark squares, such as after} 31. f3 Qd4 {.}) 31. Kg2 Bc1 32. Nd3 {EXERCISE:
Try to put yourself in the black bishop's shoes. Which diagonal would you
ideally like to be on and how do you get there? --- ANSWER:} Bd2 {Heading for
the b6-f2 diagonal!} 33. Bf3 Ba5 34. b4 Bb6 35. a4 Qc4 36. Qe4 Qc2 37. a5 Bd4
38. Qg6 $2 {White fatally allows the central pawns to advance, possibly as a
result of time pressure.} ({I don't see anything wrong with} 38. a6 Qa2 39. b5
{as White can elegantly give up a piece:} Qb1 40. Qd5 $1 Qxd3 41. a7 Qa3 42.
a8=Q Rxa8 43. Qxa8+ Qxa8 44. Bxa8 {with a likely draw.}) 38... d5 39. Bxd5
Rxf2+ 40. Kh3 Rxh2+ 41. Kg4 h5+ {. Summary: It was interesting to note the way
that Shirov played around the strong knight on d5, undermining it in order to
preserve his bishop-pair. Try to force yourself to constantly reassess the
situation on the board and ask yourself questions about the activity of your
pieces. Make them happier and your games will improve!} 0-1

