{In the next game we will see how Black, some 500 rating points higher than
his opponent, wrests control of important squares and thus improves his minor
pieces significantly.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6.
Bg5 e6 7. f4 h6 $5 {Quite a useful way of avoiding some of the main lines of
the Bg5 Najdorf.} 8. Bh4 Be7 9. Qf3 Nbd7 10. O-O-O Qc7 11. g4 $6 {EXERCISE:
Stop and evaluate the position. Pay particular attention to the minor pieces.
It appears as though all the white pieces are superior to the black ones. Can
you find a way to challenge this assessment? --- ANSWER: Evaluating: 1)
Material is equal. --- 2) White's king is more secure than Black's at the
moment and it is hard to see Black castling into that mass of white kingside
pawns. --- 3) White has five pieces developed to Black's four (though it is
Black to move). --- 4) White has more space. --- 5) All of the white pieces
that are developed are more actively placed than their counterparts. ---
QUESTION: How can the assessment of this position be anything other than White
is better? --- ANSWER: Gundavaa latches on to the concept of control of a very
important central square and his pieces come to life.} (11. Bd3 g5 12. fxg5 Ne5
13. Qe2 Nfg4 {is a better way to allow the black pawn break.}) 11... g5 $1 {A
very nice idea! Black uses the slightly exposed position of the h4-bishop to
gain control of the e5-square for his knight.} 12. fxg5 (12. e5 $5 {leads to a
complete mess, but it is a fascinating way to block the e- square and is a
very principled way to play, trying to open up lines to the black king. After}
dxe5 13. fxg5 hxg5 14. Bg3 Rb8 15. h4 gxh4 16. g5 Nd5 (16... Nh5 $2 17. g6 $1 {
was clearly better for White in I.Smolkov-A.Areshchenko, Alushta 2002}) 17.
Nxd5 Bxg5+ 18. Kb1 exd5 19. Qxd5 Bf6 {Black is hanging on by a thread.}) 12...
Ne5 13. Qg3 Nfxg4 14. gxh6 Bxh4 15. Qxh4 {QUESTION: Black's knights have come
to life, but his king is still in some danger. How can Black deal with this?
--- ANSWER:} Qe7 $1 {A fine move, offering to exchange the queens or seize
control of the g5-square.} 16. Qxe7+ (16. Qg3 {should probably have been
preferred, but after} Qg5+ 17. Kb1 Qe3 $1 {Black's queen will not take 'no'
for an answer!}) 16... Kxe7 17. Rd2 Rxh6 {EXERCISE: Re-evaluate the position.
Who is better here, by how much and why? --- ANSWER: An evaluation: 1)
Material is equal. --- 2) Neither king looks in any real trouble as the queens
have been exchanged. --- 3) The telling factors here are the pawn structure
and the activity of the pieces. --- 4) I would say that both black knights are
superior to their white counterparts. There are no access points for either
white knight due to the black pawn structure covering the important squares d5,
f5 and b5. The c3-knight could make a play for the b6-square, however. The
black knights have a brighter future due to weaknesses on the squares c4, e3,
f3 and f2. --- 5) The rook on h6 is excellently placed, targeting the weak
white h-pawn and the other black rook can back it up or occupy the open c- or
g-files. --- 6) In the endgame, as we know, the pawn structure becomes a more
telling factor. Here Black has two pawn islands to White's three. The h-pawn
is passed (and therefore must be kept an eye on), but also a target for attack.
Of bigger concern is the isolated e4-pawn, which if it falls will give Black a
huge central pawn majority. --- Conclusion: for these reasons we can assess
this position as clearly better for Black.} 18. h3 Bd7 {Preventing the white
knight from accessing a4, whilst preparing for the development of the a8-rook.}
19. Nd1 Nf6 {Black targets the weaknesses in the white position.} 20. Bg2 Rg8
21. Ne3 $2 {This natural looking move is a mistake, as White forgets about the
defence of his e4-pawn momentarily.} (21. Re1 {would have been better. Black
could continue to build up slowly here with something like} Rh4 22. Nc3 b5 23.
a3 Bc8 $1 {, looking to transfer the bishop to the long diagonal.}) 21... Rh4
$1 {Now the e4-pawn falls.} 22. Ne2 Nxe4 23. Rd4 d5 24. Bxe4 dxe4 {Gundavaa
doesn't want to ease the pressure on his lower-rated opponent's position by
exchanging a pair of rooks. The h4-rook also keeps the white h-pawn in check.}
25. Nc3 Rg3 26. Nc4 Nxc4 27. Rxc4 f5 $6 (27... Bc6 {would have been much
simpler, depriving White of any counterplay on the seventh rank.}) 28. Rc7 $1
Kd6 29. Rxb7 Bc6 30. Rb6 (30. Rd1+ Ke5 31. Rb6 Be8 {should be winning for
Black, although the king on e5 isn't all that comfortably placed.}) 30... Rgxh3
31. Rd1+ Kc7 32. Rxa6 Rxc3 $2 {Rather an unnecessary exchange sacrifice.} ({
Much simpler would have been} 32... e3 33. Ra7+ Bb7 34. Ne2 f4 {when the black
pawns are going to touch down.}) 33. bxc3 e3 34. Ra7+ Bb7 35. Re1 (35. Rd4 $1 {
seems to be the most tenacious defence here:} Rh1+ 36. Rd1 Rh7 37. Ra5 $1 {
looking to get to the e5-square when the game is very much still alive.}) 35...
f4 36. Rg1 Kb6 37. Ra4 {EXERCISE: Can you find a cute way to finish the game
here? --- ANSWER:} f3 $1 38. Rxh4 f2 39. Rb4+ Kc5 (39... Ka7 $4 {would throw
away all the hard work after} 40. Rg7 f1=Q+ 41. Kb2 Qa6 42. Rbxb7+ Qxb7+ 43.
Rxb7+ Kxb7 44. Kc1 {with a winning king and pawn ending for White.}) 40. Rf1 e2
{A triumph for the central pawns!} 41. Rxf2 e1=Q+ 42. Kb2 Qxf2 43. Rxb7 e5 44.
Rb4 Qf3 45. a4 e4 46. a5 e3 47. a6 e2 {. Summary: Dynamic pawn play by Black
gave his minor pieces excellent central squares which proved very important.
When making evaluations of piece activity be aware of the dynamic ways to
fight for control of the important squares for the pieces, as with 11...g5
here.} 0-1

