1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 $2 {A basic error.} ({The main line Petroff
defence runs} 3... d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 {.} ({. Here} 5. Qe2 $6 {is a
surprisingly common continuation I see:} Qe7 6. d3 $6 Nf6 {with a completely
equal game.}) ({. However,} 5. Nc3 $5 {is a pretty handy alternative to try
and unbalance the game:} Nxc3 (5... d5 $6 6. Qe2 $1 {is strong}) 6. dxc3 Be7 7.
Be3 {followed by Qd2 and 0-0-0.})) 4. Qe2 Qe7 ({At least Black didn't compound
his error with} 4... Nf6 $4 5. Nc6+ {.}) 5. Qxe4 d6 6. Bc4 $2 {Adam didn't
want an extra pawn!} (6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5 {is just that - an extra pawn for no
compensation.}) 6... Qxe5 7. Qxe5+ dxe5 8. O-O Bf5 9. d3 Nd7 10. Nc3 a6 {
EXERCISE: Can you make use of your slight lead in development here? --- ANSWER:
} 11. f4 $1 {Commendably with the black king still in the centre, White tries
to open up the e- and f-files.} (11. Nd5 $6 {looks tempting, but allows Black
an easy game with} O-O-O {.}) 11... Bc5+ 12. Kh1 Bg6 13. fxe5 (13. f5 Bh5 14.
Ne4 $1 {strikes me as being more natural, trying to play against the misplaced
bishop on h5 as 15 Ng3 is threatened.}) 13... Nxe5 14. Re1 f6 15. Bf4 O-O-O 16.
Bxe5 fxe5 17. Rxe5 Bd4 {White has won a pawn, but Black has the bishop pair as
some compensation.} 18. Ree1 Rhf8 {EXERCISE: A spot of prophylaxis for you!
What is Black threatening and what can White do to prevent this threat? ---
ANSWER:} 19. Rf1 {A good move, stopping the invasion of the rook to f2.} h5 $6
{The start of a mistaken plan. This gives White time to organize his queenside
pieces. There are no targets on the kingside so this plan is flawed.} (19...
Rde8 {seems much more natural to me.}) 20. Rab1 h4 21. Nd5 Bh5 22. c3 Bc5 23.
Nf4 Bg4 24. Be6+ Bxe6 25. Nxe6 Rxf1+ 26. Rxf1 Rd5 {QUESTION: We now find White
a pawn up with the move in an endgame, with a decision to make: to exchange
the knight for the bishop or not?} 27. Nxc5 $2 {ANSWER: The desire to remove
the supposedly superior bishop is not the best. Notice how play now also
enters a single rook endgame. Remember Dr Tarrasch's words? Watch what happens
here!} (27. d4 Be7 28. Nxg7 {is much cleaner. It gives White two extra pawns
and the black bishop is hampered by the white pawn chain.}) 27... Rxc5 28. d4
Rc6 29. Rf8+ Kd7 30. Rf7+ Kd8 31. Rxg7 $2 {From a practical point of view this
is a serious error. White fails to consider Black's counterplay.} ({The
strongest move was} 31. Kg1 $1 {which prevents the opponent's rook from
invading on the second rank:} g6 (31... Re6 32. Kf2 {is the point}) 32. Kf2 Re6
33. Rh7 {.}) 31... Re6 $1 {Now there will be a race on, as the rook will start
eating the white queenside pawns.} 32. h3 {It is important to recognize there
a race is about to start and thus push the pawns as every tempo is crucial,} ({
although} 32. g4 $1 hxg3 33. Rxg3 Re1+ 34. Rg1 Re2 35. Rb1 Kd7 {is still going
to be difficult to win.}) 32... Re2 33. Rg4 Rxb2 34. Rxh4 Rxa2 {The problem
for Adam now is that there are three possible results in the game. Black, from
nowhere, has obtained some winning chances thanks to his outside passed pawn.}
35. Rf4 $1 {A good multipurpose move, preparing if necessary to defend the
c-pawn whilst freeing the kingside pawns to advance.} Ra5 36. g4 Rd5 37. c4 $6
{In a race such as this time is everything!} (37. h4 a5 38. g5 Rd6 39. h5 Rd5
40. h6 Rxg5 41. Rf2 Rg8 42. h7 Rh8 43. Rf7 $1 {wins for White, as Rg7 followed
by Rg8+ is threatened.}) 37... Rd6 38. d5 a5 39. h4 a4 {EXERCISE: The a-pawn
is fast as the black rook can support it from a6. Which is the right way for
the white rook to go? In front of the pawn or behind it? --- ANSWER:} 40. Rf8+
Ke7 41. Ra8 $4 {Following the basic endgame principle of putting the rook
behind the passed pawn, but failing to appreciate the specifics of the
position.} Ra6 {Suddenly it's over. Black is winning.} 42. Rc8 a3 43. Rxc7+ Kd6
44. Rf7 a2 45. Rf1 a1=Q 46. Rxa1 Rxa1+ 47. Kg2 Rc1 48. h5 Rxc4 49. Kf3 Kxd5 50.
g5 Ke6 51. h6 Rh4 ({White resigned, as after} 51... Rh4 52. Kg3 Rh1 53. Kg4 b5
{he cannot make any progress on the kingside.}) (51... -- {Summary: This game
highlights two main points. --- 1) When ahead always keep focused on your
opponent's potential counterplay. With 31 Rxg7? Adam took his eye off the ball
momentarily and gave Black chances. --- 2) Try to be as concrete as you can on
the specifics of the position, remembering that every game is different, and
look out for small details that can make all the difference. Here White forgot
about 41...Ra6.}) 0-1

