we do with the king? --- ANSWER:} 42. Ke4 $1 {Positivity is the name of the
game here. White abandons his kingside pawns for the moment as his trump card
lies through the centre.} Bg1 43. Rb8+ Rf8 {Black cannot dare expose his king
even though he would like to keep the rooks on the board.} ({The attacking
combination of king, knight and rook is too dangerous after} 43... Kf7 44. Ne5+
Ke6 45. d4 $1 {.}) 44. Rxf8+ {A good decision. Endgames can often be won by
thinking in 'phases'. The first phase was to get the rooks off. Next will be
to secure the kingside pawns before advancing the d-pawn.} ({Instead} 44. Rxb4
$2 Bxh2 45. Rb7 Bxg3 46. Rxa7 h5 {gives Black too much counterplay and any
result is suddenly possible. The black bishop is now the superior piece as it
can be used to both support the kingside pawns and cover against the white
queenside advance.}) 44... Kxf8 45. h3 {The pawns should be placed on the
opposite-coloured squares to the enemy bishop.} Ke7 46. d4 (46. Kd5 {is also
positive and good, heading for the queenside. If} Kd7 47. Ne5+ Kc7 48. Nc6 {
wins the b-pawn.}) 46... Ke6 47. d5+ Kf6 48. Ne3 {EXERCISE: Callum wants to
free a path for his king to the queenside. What is Black's best response?} (48.
d4 {would also have been very logical, cutting off the bishop from the defence
of the queenside for the moment: for example,} Bf2 49. g4 Ke7 50. Ne5 {with
the knight heading to c6.}) ({However, White's task would be made much harder
after the hasty} 48. d6 $2 Ke6 49. d4 Bf2 50. g4 Bg3 51. d5+ Kd7 {when the
weakness of the doubled isolated pawns is apparent.}) 48... h5 {ANSWER: A good
move, trying to put some doubt into White's mind as to whether he can abandon
his kingside pawns. In a pawn race Black is now one step closer to making a
queen!} 49. Kd4 Bf2 50. g4 hxg4 (50... h4 51. Kc5 Ke5 52. d6 {is way too slow
for Black.}) 51. hxg4 Be1 52. Nc4 Bf2+ {Rotstein finds a clever way of keeping
the door shut on the white king for the moment.} 53. Ke4 Bg3 {QUESTION: How to
make progress here? --- ANSWER: Think about improving your pieces in stages.}
54. Na5 $1 {The knight simply looks for a better square on c6, where it
targets both black queenside pawns.} Bc7 {Going after the g4-pawn looks
tempting,} ({but} 54... Kg5 55. Nb7 $1 Kxg4 56. d6 {is hopeless for Black.})
55. Nc6 a5 56. Nd4 {Centralization! Here the knight sets up fork tricks which
are annoying and prevents Black winning the g4-pawn.} g6 57. g5+ $6 {Not
strictly necessary and it places the pawn on a dark square.} ({I would have
preferred} 57. Ne6 Bd6 58. Kd4 {with the plan of sending the king to c6.})
57... Ke7 58. Nc6+ Kd7 {EXERCISE: What do you make of the king and pawn ending
that could arise after 59 Ne5+?} 59. d4 ({ANSWER: The hasty} 59. Ne5+ $4 {
would be a catastrophe for White as after} Bxe5 60. Kxe5 a4 $1 {it is Black
who is suddenly winning as one of his queenside pawns touches down.}) 59... Ke8
60. Ne5 $1 Bd8 ({Now after} 60... Bxe5 61. dxe5 {the connected passed pawns
will keep the black king at bay whilst White can mop up the a5- and b4-pawns.})
61. Nxg6 Bxg5 {With the g-pawns eliminated there is very little chance of any
black counterplay. The more active white king will have a field day on the
queenside.} 62. Ne5 (62. d6 Kd7 63. Ne5+ $1 {would also be good enough due to
the fork trick} Kxd6 64. Nf7+ {.}) 62... Bd8 {QUESTION: With the g-pawns
successfully eliminated what the next phase of action be?} 63. Kd3 $6 {ANSWER:
The right idea (to bring the king to the queenside pawns),} ({but not as
positive or strong as} 63. d6 $1 {completely cutting the enemy king out of the
game.}) 63... Bb6 (63... Bc7 64. Kc4 Ke7 {is more stubborn when White should
again reroute his knight with} 65. Nd3 Bb8 66. Nc5 Ba7 67. Ne4 $1 {to control
the d6-square.}) 64. Kc4 {Now the king cannot get to d6 in time and the game
is clearly won.} Bc7 ({After} 64... Ke7 65. Kb5 $1 {again the pawn is immune
due to the knight fork:} Bxd4 66. Nc6+ {.}) 65. Kb5 Ke7 {EXERCISE: One more
accurate move, to prevent any Black activity, should be enough. What is it?
--- ANSWER:} 66. Nc4 {Controlling the d6-square and not allowing the black
king into the game.} Kd7 67. d6 $1 {Here White still needed to be careful and
not relax!} (67. Nxa5 $4 Kd6 {was the one last trick that the wily GM was
playing for. He would then win both d-pawns when the game should be a draw.})
67... Bd8 68. Nxa5 {Now the a-pawn is free to be captured and the knight fork
on b7 means d6 is also safe.} Bh4 69. Nc4 Bg3 70. Kc5 (70. Kxb4 {also wins.})
70... Ke6 71. Kc6 Bh4 72. Ne3 Bd8 73. Nd5 Ba5 74. Nc7+ Kf7 75. Kb5 {.
Domination of the bishop by the knight! Not something you see every day.} (75.
-- {Summary: A nicely played endgame! Callum remained positive throughout,
striving for maximum activity and trusting his trump cards. It also highlights
the idea of thinking 'in phases' in the ending and how a bishop is not always
superior to a knight on an open board!}) 1-0

