1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 {Unquestionably the
most aggressive move against the Najdorf. White looks to double the black
pawns on f6.} e6 7. f4 Qb6 {And this is the most principled reply, challenging
the weakened white queenside at an early stage. Warning: playing this
variation requires a lot of knowledge!} 8. Qd2 {White takes up the gauntlet,
sacrificing the b2-pawn for a lead in development.} (8. Nb3 {takes the knight
off its most dangerous square and leads to quieter play: for instance,} Nbd7 9.
Qf3 Qc7 10. O-O-O b5 11. a3 Bb7 {, as in V.Akopian-L.Van Wely, Cap d'Agde 
(rapid) 1996.}) 8... Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. e5 {The most direct move, which has
undergone a resurgence of interest in recent years.} ({The sharpest
alternative is} 10. f5 {and here after} Nc6 11. fxe6 fxe6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. e5
$5 {is a very interesting move. Many variations of the Poisoned Pawn have now
been worked out to a forced draw. Here are the moves of one such example:} dxe5
14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Ne4 Qxa2 16. Rd1 Be7 17. Be2 O-O 18. O-O Ra7 19. Rf3 Kh8 20.
Rg3 Rd7 21. Qh6 Rf7 22. Qh5 Rxd1+ 23. Bxd1 Qa5 24. Kf1 Qd8 25. Qxf7 Qxd1+ 26.
Kf2 Qxc2+ 27. Kf3 Qd1+ 28. Kf2 Qc2+ 29. Ke3 Bc5+ 30. Nxc5 Qxc5+ 31. Kd2 Qf2+
32. Kc3 Qd4+ 33. Kc2 Qf2+ 34. Kc3 {½-½ F.Vallejo Pons-G.Kasparov, Moscow
2004.}) 10... dxe5 11. fxe5 Nfd7 12. Bc4 $6 {EXERCISE: White has a big lead in
development, so Black must act with caution. What do you make of 12...Nxe5?} (
12. Ne4 {is the most testing move here, first introduced into practise by Paul
Keres in the late 1950's. After} h6 $1 13. Bh4 Qxa2 14. Rd1 Qd5 {a heavily
discussed theoretical position is reached, which we will leave for another day!
}) 12... Bb4 $1 {Gaining a tempo with development.} ({ANSWER:} 12... Nxe5 $6 {
is highly risky! Amazingly the only game according to Mega Database 2012 with
this move was played by Tringov himself a year prior to this game. That game
went} {that game went} 13. Nxe6 Qa5 14. Bd8 {when Black has to be on his toes
to survive, but} (14. Bb5+ $5 {might be the way forward:} Bd7 15. Bxd7+ Nbxd7
16. Nxf8 Rxf8 17. O-O {with lasting compensation based upon the weakness of
the black king}) 14... Nf3+ $1 15. gxf3 Qe5+ 16. Ne4 fxe6 {was eventually
drawn in J.Bednarski-G.Tringov, Kecsemet Zonal 1964.}) 13. Rb3 Qa5 14. O-O O-O
{Again Fischer refuses the second pawn. There is a line that even he dare not
cross!} (14... Nxe5 {allows the disruptive sacrifice} 15. Rxb4 $1 Qxb4 16. Nxe6
{which looks crushing for White, but the ice cold defence} Qb6+ 17. Be3 Nxc4 $1
{seems to just about hold: for example,} 18. Nxg7+ Kf8 19. Rxf7+ Kxf7 20. Qd5+
Kxg7 21. Bxb6 Nxb6 22. Qd4+ Kg8 23. Qxb6 Nc6 {with a bizarre material
imbalance.}) 15. Nxe6 {Very scary, but the art of good defence is to stay cool
and not panic, even if something happens on the board that you have not seen.
I'm guessing, though, that Fischer had, of course, seen this particular
sacrifice and knew it to be unsound.} fxe6 16. Bxe6+ Kh8 17. Rxf8+ Bxf8 18. Qf4
Nc6 (18... Qxe5 {would give the piece back and reach an approximately level
ending after} 19. Qxe5 Nxe5 20. Bxc8 b5 {.}) 19. Qf7 {EXERCISE: Find a way to
defend against the threat of Qg8 mate. Bear in mind that Black is currently a
knight for a pawn up... --- ANSWER:} Qc5+ 20. Kh1 Nf6 $1 {Beautifully done.
Black generates counterplay based on the weakness of the white back rank and
the loose bishop on g5.} 21. Bxc8 (21. exf6 Bxe6 22. Qxe6 Qxg5 {would also be
winning for Black.}) 21... Nxe5 (21... Rxc8 22. Bxf6 Qe3 $1 {would do the job
too.}) 22. Qe6 Neg4 {. The white attack has been stopped in its tracks and
Black has the decisive attack.} (22... -- {Summary: The first principle of
successful defence is to remain calm under pressure. Here Fischer calculated
accurately and saw through the white aggression. At the right moment he could
return some of his extra material in order to defuse the attack. We will
revisit this 'money in the bank' strategy later in the chapter.}) 0-1

