{Opposite-Coloured Bishops: Endgames with opposite-coloured bishops tend to be
quite drawish in nature, due to two reasons. One is the inability of the
bishops to be exchanged and the other is the way that a bishop can stop passed
pawns in their tracks along a diagonal, sometimes even if they are in vast
numbers. This can lead to some interesting fortress positions where it is
impossible for the side with the extra pawns to break through. --- Here White,
despite being two pawns up, cannot make any progress due to the fixed nature
of the pawn chain.} 1. Bd6 Bf3 2. Kc5 Ke6 3. Bc7 Be4 {, etc. One of the key
features of a fortress position is the lack of pawn breaks available.} *

